"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797647","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-12-07","<p>The Department estimates that around 270,000 cases need to be looked at again and that around 75,000 of those cases (5% of the population transferred over from incapacity benefits) may have been underpaid. The Department has already started contacting individuals to establish if there has been an underpayment of premiums and a small number of claims have already been corrected and the arrears that are due have been paid. The Department expects to complete the review and correct cases by April 2019. We will update the House shortly.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-12-07T14:20:14.077Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797647/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797647/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797647/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-29","Employment and Support Allowance: Maladministration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the answer of 28 November 2017 to Question 115232, how many claimants of Employment and Support Allowance were subject to payment miscalculations in each (a) 2011, (b) 2012, (c) 2013, (d) 2014 and (e) 2015, and what the timetable is for those claimant to be reimbursed.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","116610"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797648","Department of Health","false","2017-12-07","<p>The Department adheres to transparent Government guidelines and publishes quarterly returns on Ministerial meetings with external organisations. The most recent data, for 2017, is available at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/ministerial-gifts-hospitality-travel-and-external-meetings-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/ministerial-gifts-hospitality-travel-and-external-meetings-2017</a></p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-12-07T15:41:16.773Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797648/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797648/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797648/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-29","Department of Health: Legatum Institute","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, meetings Ministers of his Department have had with representatives of the Legatum Institute in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","116611"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797649","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-05","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The responses to the call for evidence are currently being analysed and a response will be published in due course.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-12-05T10:47:04.3Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797649/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797649/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797649/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-29","Companies: Ownership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the timetable is for bringing forward legislative proposals to require the publication of details relating to the beneficial ownership of companies buying residential property in the UK.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","116612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797650","HM Treasury","false","2017-12-05","<p>HMRC takes all reports of potential tax underpayment seriously, and thoroughly analyse and investigate any information that they receive. Where there is suspected potential tax fraud, HMRC will not hesitate to work with their prosecuting partners to bring cases before the courts.</p><p>Since 2010, HMRC has generated more than £160 billion of additional yield from tackling tax avoidance, evasion and non-compliance.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-12-05T16:04:45.17Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797650/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797650/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797650/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-29","Appleby: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans he has to check the legality of the tax schemes detailed in the Paradise Papers.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","116613"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797651","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2017-12-04","<p>In order to meet the motion of 1st November, we have taken time to bring together the sectoral analyses in a way that is accessible and informative to the Committee. We have not edited or redacted reports. At the time the motion was passed, and subsequently, we were clear that the documents did not exist in the form requested.</p><p>The Government has to be mindful of its obligations not to allow sensitive information to be public, so we have sought not to include commercially, market and negotiation sensitive information, but we have been as open as possible. The material we have provided to the Select Committee is very substantial.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-12-04T16:54:24.893Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797651/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797651/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797651/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2017-11-29","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Oral Statement of 28 November 2017, Official Report, column 161, on leaving the EU: sectoral impact assessments,  how many pages of material have been withheld in addition to the 850 pages submitted to the Exiting the European Union Committee.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","116614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797652","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-12-06","<p>There were no meetings between Ministry of Defence Ministers and representatives of the Legatum Institute in the last 12 months.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-12-06T15:34:49.853Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797652/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797652/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797652/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-29","Ministry of Defence: Legatum Institute","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what meetings Ministers of his Department have had with representatives of the Legatum Institute in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","116615"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797653","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-12-07","<p>The Autumn Budget 2017 document sets out the costs of announced policy decisions, including the additional investment for in-work progression trials in Universal Credit. This can be found the gov.uk website (on page 28):</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/661480/autumn_budget_2017_web.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/661480/autumn_budget_2017_web.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The figures published in the table are rounded to the nearest £5m in any year.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-12-07T12:51:32.08Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797653/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797653/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797653/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-29","Low Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will publish a breakdown of the £8 million investment announced in the Autumn Budget for in-work support for low-paid workers on universal credit.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","116616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797654","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-12-07","<p>There has been one meeting between current Ministers of the Ministry of Justice and representatives of the Legatum Institute in the past 12 months.</p><p><br> I attended a dinner on prison reform on 31 October 2017. The event took place at the Legatum Institute but was hosted and organised by Catch22, a not-for-profit business. Danny Kruger, a Senior Fellow at the Legatum Institute, attended this meeting.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-12-07T14:57:19.64Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797654/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797654/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797654/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-29","Ministry of Justice: Legatum Institute","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what meetings that Ministers of his Department have had with representatives of the Legatum Institute in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","116617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797655","Cabinet Office","false","2017-12-21","<p>Details of meetings that Cabinet Office Ministers have had with external organisations are published on a quarterly basis on GOV.UK.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-12-21T11:16:37.76Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797655/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797655/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797655/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-11-29","Cabinet Office: Legatum Institute","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what meetings Ministers of his Department have had with representatives of the Legatum Institute in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","116618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797656","Attorney General","false","2017-12-14","<p>Neither I nor the Solicitor General have had any meetings with representatives of the Legatum Institute in the last 12 months.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2017-12-14T14:20:51.603Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797656/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797656/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797656/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-11-29","Attorney General: Legatum Institute","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what meetings he has had with representatives of the Legatum Institute in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","116619"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797657","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-12-04","<p>As at 30 September 2017, the population of prisoners serving Imprisonment for Public Protection (IPP) sentences in prisons in England and Wales was 3,162. Of these prisoners, 2,718 have passed their minimum tariff period.These and other statistics specific to those serving indeterminate sentences are published quarterly by the Ministry of Justice here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/offender-management-statistics-quarterly" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/offender-management-statistics-quarterly</a></p><p> </p><p>I remain committed to ensuring IPP prisoners are able to progress towards release as soon it is safe to do so after their tariff has expired. IPP prisoners are achieving release in high numbers. In the year 2016/17, 46% of IPP prisoners achieved a release decision from the Parole Board, with a further 24% securing a progressive move to open conditions. Less than a third of hearings resulted in a negative outcome.</p><p> </p><p>A joint action plan is in place, co-owned by Her Majesty’s Prison and Probation Service (HMPPS) and the Parole Board, with the specific aim of providing as many opportunities for IPP prisoners to progress to safe release as soon as possible. A key part of the action plan has been to ensure that the parole process runs as smoothly as possible so as to provide IPP prisoners with timely access to parole reviews. The Parole Board has effectively eliminated its backlog and is now listing more hearings than ever before.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","116621","2017-12-04T13:38:18.483Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797657/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797657/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797657/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-29","Prison Sentences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prisoners imprisoned for public protection remain imprisioned; and if will he make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","116620"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797658","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-12-04","<p>As at 30 September 2017, the population of prisoners serving Imprisonment for Public Protection (IPP) sentences in prisons in England and Wales was 3,162. Of these prisoners, 2,718 have passed their minimum tariff period.These and other statistics specific to those serving indeterminate sentences are published quarterly by the Ministry of Justice here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/offender-management-statistics-quarterly" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/offender-management-statistics-quarterly</a></p><p> </p><p>I remain committed to ensuring IPP prisoners are able to progress towards release as soon it is safe to do so after their tariff has expired. IPP prisoners are achieving release in high numbers. In the year 2016/17, 46% of IPP prisoners achieved a release decision from the Parole Board, with a further 24% securing a progressive move to open conditions. Less than a third of hearings resulted in a negative outcome.</p><p> </p><p>A joint action plan is in place, co-owned by Her Majesty’s Prison and Probation Service (HMPPS) and the Parole Board, with the specific aim of providing as many opportunities for IPP prisoners to progress to safe release as soon as possible. A key part of the action plan has been to ensure that the parole process runs as smoothly as possible so as to provide IPP prisoners with timely access to parole reviews. The Parole Board has effectively eliminated its backlog and is now listing more hearings than ever before.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","116620","2017-12-04T13:38:18.547Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797658/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797658/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797658/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-29","Prison Sentences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps his Department is taking to bring forward the parole hearings of prisoners imprisonment for public protection who have exceeded their minimum term in prison?","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","116621"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797659","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-12-07","<p>The United Kingdom has sentence enforcement agreements with a number of international courts and tribunals. Under these arrangements the UK is currently holding one person convicted of war crimes by the Special Court for Sierra Leone.</p><p> </p><p>Previously three prisoners convicted of war crimes by the International Criminal Tribunal for the Former Yugoslavia (ICTY) have served all or part of their sentence in the United Kingdom in the last 10 years. A further prisoner convicted by ICTY was held here prior to this period. These four prisoners are no longer detained in the UK.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","116713","2017-12-07T16:24:41.21Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797659/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797659/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797659/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-29","War Crimes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people convicted of war crimes are detained in the UK; and how many people have been so detained in the last 10 years?","false","Biography information for Jared O'Mara","Sheffield, Hallam","Jared O'Mara","116622"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797660","Department of Health","false","2017-12-07","<p>The Government takes seriously the issue of the misuse of opioid substances. In July we published a comprehensive new drug strategy setting out a balanced approach to tackling drug abuse, including opioid abuse, which brings together police, health, community and global partners to tackle the illicit drugs trade, protect the most vulnerable and help those with drug dependency to recover and turn their lives around. The Department leads on the Building Recovery strand and co-leads, with the Home Office, on the Reducing Demand strand of the cross-Government Drug Strategy. The strategy can be accessed at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/drug-strategy-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/drug-strategy-2017</a></p><p>We are committed to ensuring that anyone with a drug problem can access the help and support they need to overcome it. Local authorities are responsible for commissioning drug treatment services to meet the needs of their population and they are supported in this by Public Health England through the provision of data, guidance and targeted support.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-12-07T15:08:31.067Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797660/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797660/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797660/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-29","Opiates: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to tackle opioid abuse?","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","116623"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797661","Department for International Development","false","2017-12-04","<p>Data for all DFID’s spend is available in the Statistics for International Development publication at</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-on-international-development" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-on-international-development</a>. The figures for 2016 have just been released and those for 2017 will be released next year. Allocations for future years will be confirmed in due course. SID does not differentiate between DFID’s spend in the West Bank and Gaza.</p><p>The UK provided more than £17 million in immediate humanitarian assistance for those affected by the Gaza conflict in the summer of 2014. In October 2014, the UK pledged, and subsequently fully disbursed a further £20 million in early recovery assistance at the Gaza Reconstruction Conference in Cairo, including support for cash assistance to Palestinian refugees, mine removal and medical treatment. More recently the UK provided £1.9 million of humanitarian assistance to the United Nations Children’s Fund (UNICEF) in Gaza to address critical water, sanitation and hygiene needs, benefitting approximately 1 million people. In addition the UK is a long-term supporter of United Nations Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees (UNRWA) which provides basic services to 1.3 million people in Gaza including basic health care, and we are supporting humanitarian access, enabling reconstruction efforts and investing in job creation in Gaza.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-12-04T15:46:36.663Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797661/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797661/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797661/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-11-29","Gaza: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much her Department has spent on humanitarian aid to the Gaza strip in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","116624"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797662","Department for International Development","false","2017-12-04","<p>The UK is supporting approximately 1 million Gazans by addressing critical water, sanitation and hygiene needs, as identified in the UN Gaza Urgent Funding Appeal, through a £1.9m grant to the United Nations Children’s Fund. In addition the UK is a long-term supporter of United Nations Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees (UNRWA) which provides basic services to 1.3 million people in Gaza including basic health care, and we are supporting humanitarian access, enabling reconstruction efforts and investing in job creation in Gaza.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-12-04T15:44:32.583Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797662/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797662/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797662/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-11-29","Gaza: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to support the UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs humanitarian funding appeal to support people in Gaza.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","116625"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797663","Department of Health","false","2017-12-04","<p>There are two policies relating to Sapropterin (Kuvan). The first allows for access to sapropterin for women with phenylketonuria (PKU) who are pregnant and cannot maintain appropriate PKU levels with their diet. This can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/commissioning/spec-services/npc-crg/group-e/e09/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/commissioning/spec-services/npc-crg/group-e/e09/</a></p><p>For the remaining patients, sapropterin is not routinely funded. This policy can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/commissioning/spec-services/npc-crg/group-e/e06/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/commissioning/spec-services/npc-crg/group-e/e06/</a></p><p> </p><p>This second policy is currently in the process of being reviewed, with a decision expected in 2018. This will involve evaluating any new clinical evidence that has been developed since this policy was originally formed.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has a number of mechanisms available to secure access to medicines in secondary care from pharmaceutical companies. For example, the Commercial Medicines Unit undertakes procurements through framework agreements that enable individual trusts to purchase medicines at the framework price. Where medicines have been approved by the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence, a patient access scheme may be in place to allow the National Health Service to benefit from a discounted price. The mechanism used will depend on the medicine in any given case.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","116628","2017-12-04T17:08:51.763Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797663/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797663/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797663/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-29","Sapropterin","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether he has plans to increase access to sapropterin for phenylketonuria.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","116626"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797664","Department for International Development","false","2017-12-06","<p>The UK is working closely with its partners to provide protection services to Rohingya child refugees in Bangladesh. As part of wider efforts, UK aid is funding trauma counselling services include psychosocial and psychological support for 7,500 children. In addition to identifying unaccompanied and separated children, we are also supporting the Red Cross to provide family linking and family tracing services. Child protection support includes establishment of 30 child friendly spaces and supporting children to learn and adopt safe behaviours in settlements.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","116629 ; 116634","2017-12-06T16:02:52.397Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797664/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797664/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797664/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-11-29","Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps she is taking to support trauma counselling services for child Rohingya refugees?","true","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","116627"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797665","Department of Health","false","2017-12-04","<p>There are two policies relating to Sapropterin (Kuvan). The first allows for access to sapropterin for women with phenylketonuria (PKU) who are pregnant and cannot maintain appropriate PKU levels with their diet. This can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/commissioning/spec-services/npc-crg/group-e/e09/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/commissioning/spec-services/npc-crg/group-e/e09/</a></p><p>For the remaining patients, sapropterin is not routinely funded. This policy can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/commissioning/spec-services/npc-crg/group-e/e06/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/commissioning/spec-services/npc-crg/group-e/e06/</a></p><p> </p><p>This second policy is currently in the process of being reviewed, with a decision expected in 2018. This will involve evaluating any new clinical evidence that has been developed since this policy was originally formed.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has a number of mechanisms available to secure access to medicines in secondary care from pharmaceutical companies. For example, the Commercial Medicines Unit undertakes procurements through framework agreements that enable individual trusts to purchase medicines at the framework price. Where medicines have been approved by the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence, a patient access scheme may be in place to allow the National Health Service to benefit from a discounted price. The mechanism used will depend on the medicine in any given case.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","116626","2017-12-04T17:08:51.903Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797665/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797665/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797665/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-29","Phenylketonuria: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether he plans to allow NHS England to negotiate directly with pharmaceutical companies to improve access to treatments for phenylketonuria.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","116628"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797666","Department for International Development","false","2017-12-06","<p>The UK is working closely with its partners to provide protection services to Rohingya child refugees in Bangladesh. As part of wider efforts, UK aid is funding trauma counselling services include psychosocial and psychological support for 7,500 children. In addition to identifying unaccompanied and separated children, we are also supporting the Red Cross to provide family linking and family tracing services. Child protection support includes establishment of 30 child friendly spaces and supporting children to learn and adopt safe behaviours in settlements.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","116627 ; 116634","2017-12-06T16:02:52.443Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797666/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797666/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797666/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-11-29","Bangladesh: Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps she is taking to support child protection services for Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh?","false","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","116629"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797667","Department for International Development","false","2017-12-06","<p>DFID is one of the biggest donors to the Rohingya refugee crisis in Bangladesh. DFID has worked for many years in Cox's Bazar and has stepped up efforts with an additional £59 million to support the latest influx of refugees. £54 million of this is being committed to respond to needs identified in the UN-led Humanitarian Response Plan.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-12-06T16:06:04.093Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797667/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797667/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797667/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-11-29","Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps she is taking to contribute to funding of the Humanitarian Support Plan for Rohingya refugees?","false","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","116630"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797668","Department for International Development","false","2017-12-06","<p>Ensuring access to services and assistance for all vulnerable people, including people living with disabilities, is central to DFID’s approach. UK aid is supporting targeted assistance for disabled people, including outreach services providing cooked food, and cash or vouchers for essential purchases. UK assistance is supporting the provision of disabled-access emergency latrines to an estimated 70,000 people. Reducing distances to service points, increasing access into the camps, strengthening referral systems, and increasing access to information as the response continues to scale up will also support the disabled population.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-12-06T16:07:31.21Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797668/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797668/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797668/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-11-29","Bangladesh: Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps she is taking to provide humanitarian support for disabled Rohingya refugees in camps in Bangladesh?","true","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","116631"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797669","Department for International Development","false","2017-12-06","<p>The UK is one of the largest donors to the crisis, providing support of £59m since the end of August. We are ensuring effective help is being provided for Rohingya refugees in the medium and longer term, as well caring for immediate needs. Of the £12m of new funding announced for the crisis at the end of last month, £8m will help ensure assistance is sustained after the months up to February 2018 covered by the current UN appeal, including helping improve security for women and girls. We have also provided shelter for over 130,000 people and support to make shelters more weather resistant for 450,000 people.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-12-06T16:04:58.24Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797669/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797669/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797669/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-11-29","Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what progress her Department is making in the provision of long-term facilities such as shelters for Rohingya refugees.","false","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","116632"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797670","Department for International Development","false","2017-12-06","<p>The Education Cannot Wait initiative has committed US$3 million (£2.2 million) for Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh. This will help cover more than 70 percent of the emergency educational needs of Rohingya refugee children until the end of 2017. DFID is developing an ambitious new education policy to ensure that the most marginalised children begin learning now. We are reviewing options for further funding as part of our longer term response to the Rohingya refugee crisis.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-12-06T16:08:37.127Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797670/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797670/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797670/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-11-29","Bangladesh: Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to ensure access to education for child Rohingya refugees in camps in Bangladesh?","false","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","116633"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797671","Department for International Development","false","2017-12-06","<p>The UK is working closely with its partners to provide protection services to Rohingya child refugees in Bangladesh. As part of wider efforts, UK aid is funding trauma counselling services include psychosocial and psychological support for 7,500 children. In addition to identifying unaccompanied and separated children, we are also supporting the Red Cross to provide family linking and family tracing services. Child protection support includes establishment of 30 child friendly spaces and supporting children to learn and adopt safe behaviours in settlements.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","116627 ; 116629","2017-12-06T16:02:52.507Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797671/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797671/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797671/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-11-29","Bangladesh: Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what support her Department is providing to ensure safety of unaccompanied Rohingya child refugees in Bangladesh?","false","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","116634"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797672","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-06","<p>As with all recent franchise awards, Stagecoach Group PLC committed parent company support to inject funds into the franchise in circumstances where it doesn’t perform as predicted. We will hold them to that commitment in full.</p><p> </p><p>From 2020 we intend to re-let the franchise as the East Coast Partnership, one of the first of a new generation of integrated regional rail operations. This will include appropriate contributions from the new private partner under a long-term competitively procured contract.</p><p> </p><p>We are always looking for the best ways to achieve value for money for the taxpayer and the best results for passengers. Reforms will build on the best of the public and private sectors, with private sector involvement bringing innovation, investment and competition.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-12-06T17:45:32.17Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797672/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797672/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797672/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-29","East Coast Rail Franchise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of the early termination of the East Coast rail franchise?","false","Biography information for Jared O'Mara","Sheffield, Hallam","Jared O'Mara","116635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797673","Department for International Development","false","2017-12-06","<p>The UK is working closely with our partners to provide targeted protection services to Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh, including through a network of local organisations which help people to access services in a language they can easily understand, including in local dialects. We are also providing translators where needed. Examples of the help being provided includes psychosocial and psychological support for 7,500 children, and supporting the Red Cross to provide family-linking and family-tracing services.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-12-06T16:10:10.69Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797673/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797673/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797673/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-11-29","Bangladesh: Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps are being taken to ensure counselling services for Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh are provided in their native language.","true","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","116636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797674","Department for Education","false","2017-12-04","<p>The post-16 mathematics premium announced in the Budget will be uncapped, as we want as many pupils as possible to benefit from studying mathematics post-16. It is up to providers to decide how many students they can teach level 3 mathematics post-16, and up to, young people to decide whether they wish to continue studying the subject. Further information about the post-16 mathematics premium will be released in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-12-04T17:44:34.487Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797674/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797674/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797674/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-29","Mathematics: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to paragraph 4.24 of the Autumn Budget 2017, how many pupils she estimates will study Maths, Further Maths or Core Maths as a consequence of the payments set out in that paragraph for each year that it is available.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","116637"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797675","HM Treasury","false","2017-12-07","<p>As announced in Autumn Budget 2017, the government is confident that the Total Carbon Price, currently made up of the EU Emissions Trading Scheme and the Carbon Price Support, is set at the right level and will continue to target a similar carbon price until unabated coal is no longer used.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-12-07T13:44:57.26Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797675/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797675/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797675/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-29","Environment Protection: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if it is his Department's policy that the total carbon price should remain at present levels until 2025.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","116638"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797677","HM Treasury","false","2017-12-07","<p>The government will target a Total Carbon Price similar to current levels until unabated coal is no longer used in power generation. The Carbon Price Support rates have been legislated for up to April 2020, and indicative rates have been set until April 2021.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-12-07T13:41:25.297Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797677/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797677/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797677/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-29","Environment Protection: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the sum of the total carbon price is that will remain in place until 2025","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","116640"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797678","HM Treasury","false","2017-12-07","<p>The Total Carbon Price is currently made up of the EU Emissions Trading Scheme price and the Carbon Price Support. Membership of the EU Emissions Trading Scheme after EU Exit is subject to negotiation with the EU.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-12-07T13:43:19.343Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797678/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797678/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797678/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-29","Environment Protection: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what components make up the sum of the total carbon price that will remain in place until 2025.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","116641"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797679","Department for Education","false","2017-12-04","<p>Responsibility for the pay and conditions of support staff lies at a local level with head teachers and school employers. They are best placed to use their professional judgement to set support staff terms and conditions.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-12-04T17:42:54.56Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797679/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797679/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797679/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-29","Schools: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to paragraph 6.27 of the Autumn Budget 2017, what plans she has to apply the revised public sector pay policy to school support staff and teaching assistants.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","116642"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797680","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-06","<p>The Energy Company Obligation is not a low-carbon electricity levy and, therefore, is unaffected by paragraph 4.51 of the Budget.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-12-06T16:21:23.227Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797680/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797680/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797680/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-29","Energy Companies Obligation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, with reference to paragraph 4.51 of the Autumn Budget 2017, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the Government’s plans for no new low-carbon electricity levies until 2025 on its plans to extend the Energy Company Obligation set out in the Clean Growth Strategy.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","116643"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797681","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-12-11","<p>Building more affordable homes is an absolute priority for this Government, which is why the Prime Minister announced on 4 October 2017 an extra £2 billion funding for affordable housing, on top of the £1.4 billion announced last year, increasing the Affordable Homes Programme 2016/21 budget to over £9 billion.</p><p>We have confirmed a long-term rent certainty for social landlords in England - creating a stable environment that is needed to support council and housing associations to build more affordable homes.</p><p>Our new Affordable Homes Programme is ramping up. Last year there were over 49,000 housing starts - indicating stronger delivery in 2017/18. The HCA and the GLA have already allocated £3.1 billion to deliver over 104,000 homes. We expect the number of starts to continue to rise.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-12-11T17:16:14.277Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797681/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797681/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797681/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-29","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to allow housing associations to increase the number of new homes they build.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","116644"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797682","Department for Education","false","2017-12-07","<p>The Department has regular meetings with music educators to discuss aspects of the National Plan for Music Education. Music teaching starts in the early years and the plan provides a template for high quality music education throughout a pupil’s education, both in and out of school, in both formal and informal settings. Our vision continues to be that children from all backgrounds and every part of England have the opportunity to learn a musical instrument; to make music with others; to learn to sing; and to have the opportunity to progress to the next level. We will continue to consider the best way of ensuring that disadvantaged children can benefit from all programmes we fund.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-12-07T17:17:33.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797682/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797682/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797682/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-29","Music: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what discussions her Department has had with music educators on the National Plan for Music Education; and whether that Plan should (a) include Early Years, (b) recognise informal pathways for young musicians and (c) continue with universal provision or be focussed on disadvantaged children.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","116645"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797683","HM Treasury","false","2017-12-04","<p>We’re committed to placing an upper limit on the value of public sector exit payments – that’s why we legislated in the 2016 Act and will be laying the necessary regulations. Before we do so, and to ensure the successful implementation of these changes, we will bring forward a consultation in the first quarter of 2018 which will run for 12 weeks.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-12-04T15:15:53.14Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797683/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797683/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797683/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-29","Public Sector: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the timetable is to bring forward the secondary legislation  to place an upper limit on the value of public sector exit payments; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","116646"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797684","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-12-04","<p>I am placing in the Library a list of material and representations which my Rt Hon Friend received before he announced on 7 November that the Government is minded to implement the locally-led proposals for improving local government in Dorset and Suffolk.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2017-12-04T17:49:05.47Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797684/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797684/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797684/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-29","Local Government: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to the Written Statement of 7 November 2017, HCWS232 on local government improvement, if he will place in the Library a list of all the material and representations he received before making his announcement.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","116647"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797685","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-12-04","<p>I refer my Hon Friend to the Written Statement made by the Secretary of State on 7 November 2017 (HCWS232).</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2017-12-04T17:50:16.997Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797685/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797685/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797685/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-29","Local Government: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Written Statement of 7 November 2017, HCWS232, on local government improvement, what further steps are needed to secure local consent.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","116648"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797686","Department of Health","false","2017-12-04","<p>We have assumed the hon. Member is referring to Spinraza. The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) received a formal ministerial referral for nusinersen (Spinraza) to treat spinal muscular atrophy and this topic has been scheduled into its work programme. The appraisal process is anticipated to begin in January 2018 and the deadline for an evidence submission is anticipated to be March 2018. Although no further details about timescales for the development of guidance are available at this stage, NICE take approximately nine months to develop guidance on new drug depending on the individual product.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-12-04T17:18:52.62Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797686/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797686/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797686/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-29","Spinal Muscular Atrophy: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the timetable is for a decision to be made on the authorisation of spinroza as an NHS treatment for people who suffer from spinal muscular atrophy; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","116649"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797687","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-04","<p>The reasons for this decision are set out in the Great Western Rail Franchise consultation document published on 29 November (in particular, the Executive Summary and paragraphs 3.11 to 3.14), available at <a href="http://www.gov.uk/dft" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/dft</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The principal reasons are to ensure that passengers get the best possible service while the current and forthcoming transformational upgrades to the Great Western franchise area are carried out, and to allow the enhanced service to bed in fully before running a competition for a new long-term franchise. This short period of “bedding in” will help to ensure that the next franchise competition attracts ambitious bids that deliver the best outcomes for passengers through the 2020s.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-12-04T17:14:36.363Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797687/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797687/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797687/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-29","Great Western Rail Franchise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the reasons are for his decision to (a) award a 12 month franchise extension and (b) offer a potential two year additional direct award to GWR.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","116650"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797688","Department of Health","false","2017-12-07","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) has been asked to develop technology appraisal guidance on the use of nusinersen (Spinraza) to treat spinal muscular atrophy and this topic has been scheduled into NICE’s work programme. The appraisal process is anticipated to begin in January 2018 and the deadline for an evidence submission is anticipated to be March 2018. Although no further details about timescales for the development of guidance are available at this stage, NICE take approximately nine months to develop guidance on a new drug depending on the individual product.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-12-07T15:10:28.443Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797688/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797688/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797688/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-29","Nusinersen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the timetable is for NICE to begin its evaluation of the spinal muscular atrophy treatment Spinraza.","false","Biography information for Alberto Costa","South Leicestershire","Alberto Costa","116651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797689","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-04","<p>We will announce further details about the challenges in wave 2 of the Industrial Strategy Challenge Fund early next year.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-12-04T17:43:48.627Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797689/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797689/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797689/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-29","Industrial Strategy Challenge Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when he plans to publish the (a) business case and (b) funding details for wave 2 projects funded through the Industrial Strategy Challenge Fund.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","116652"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797690","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-04","<p>The review will focus on what actions could be most effective in improving productivity and growth of SMEs, including how to address what has been called ‘long tail’ of lower productivity firms. We will announce the policies we intend to take forward following this review in Autumn 2018.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-12-04T17:41:32.893Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797690/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797690/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797690/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-29","Small Businesses: Productivity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the timetable is for publication of his review into improving the productivity and growth of small and medium-sized businesses.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","116653"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797691","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-04","<p>An agile approach to regulation is crucial in supporting growth among innovative firms and ensuring that we realise the benefits of new and emerging technologies for all. We will welcome applications to the fund from regulators for those sectors affected by emerging technologies.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-12-04T14:21:00.507Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797691/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797691/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797691/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-29","Regulation: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, which UK regulators will be eligible to receive funding from the proposed Regulators' Pioneer Fund.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","116654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797692","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-12-04","<p>There were 3 convictions for the illegal usage of drones in England and Wales in 2016, the latest year for which data is available. One in each of June, October and December.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-12-04T14:43:20.337Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797692/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797692/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797692/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-29","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many successful prosecutions have been made for the illegal usage of drones in each of the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","116655"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797693","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-05","<p>Government has just launched an ambitious, modern Industrial Strategy which sets out in detail a long term plan to boost the productivity and earning power of people throughout the UK and our commitment to encouraging the commercialisation of UK innovations, helping to ensure that exciting ideas are turned into strong commercial products and services. It includes two new centres to support innovation in UK cyber security as part of the National Cyber Security Strategy, a National Security Strategic Investment Fund of up to £85m to invest in advanced technologies, a transformative multi-billion pound Sector Deal with the life sciences industry to ensure that the UK remains at the forefront of innovation in this sector, our commitment to working closely with industry and academia on the Artificial Intelligence grand challenge and sector deal and a Patient Capital Review which puts £2.5b investment into innovative firms wanting to scale up.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, we are investing in strategic innovation challenges through the Industrial Strategy Challenge Fund and through the Catapult network we are bridging the gap between business, academia, research and Government on late-stage research and development to transform “high potential” ideas into new products and services to generate economic growth.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-12-05T15:05:02.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797693/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797693/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797693/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797693/answer/previousversion/26963","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-29","ICT: Innovation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps the Government is taking to encourage the commercialisation of UK innovations in (a) cybersecurity, (b) machine learning, (c) microelectronics, (d) compound chip technology and (c) biotechnology.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","116656"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797694","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-04","<p>Local Industrial Strategies will establish new ways of working between national and local leaders in both the public and private sectors, with local authorities continuing to play an integral role in shaping their economies through their contribution to the work of the Local Enterprise Partnership. We expect each local strategy to be a result of extensive consultation at a local level.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-12-04T17:44:19.393Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797694/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797694/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797694/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-29","Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what involvement local authorities will have in the development and delivery of the Local Industrial Strategies referred to in the Industrial Strategy White Paper.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","116657"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797695","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-04","<p>Following the Statutory Review of the Groceries Code Adjudicator (GCA), the Government is working with the GCA to agree a strategic goal to address the reluctance of some direct suppliers to raise legitimate grievances with the GCA due to a fear of commercial consequences. The Government will continue to support the GCA in her work by also making it clear to retailers designated by the Code that it is not acceptable that direct suppliers face commercial consequences as a result of reporting potential breaches of the Code. We will also work with Trade Associations to help their members understand how the Code works and the role of the GCA.</p><p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy has been working closely with the Department for Environment Food and Rural Affairs to consider potential solutions to issues identified by respondents to the Call for Evidence on the remit of the GCA. We aim to publish a response to the call for evidence in due course.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-12-04T14:18:17.497Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797695/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797695/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797695/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-29","Groceries Code Adjudicator","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 27 November 2017 to Question 115216, what changes he proposes to implement for the operation of the Grocery Code Adjudicator (GCA) as a result of the review published on 19 July 2017; and what plans he has to extend the remit of the GCA to cover smaller suppliers in the grocery supply chain.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","116658"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797696","HM Treasury","false","2017-12-04","<p>The Valuation Office Agency does not charge ratepayers for undertaking property valuations and has no plans to do so.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-12-04T16:16:33.75Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797696/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797696/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797696/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-29","Business Premises: Valuation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 27 November 2017 to Question 115208 on business premises: valuation, what plans he has to change the amount charged by the Valuation Office Agency to revalue properties for business rates purposes.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","116659"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797697","Department for International Trade","false","2017-12-05","<p>The department has budgeted for up to £80,000 for the recruitment of Her Britannic Majesty’s Trade Commissioners. This includes candidate attraction, recruitment and assessment costs.</p><p>These activities are standard procedure for senior positions across government and will ensure we attract a wide and diverse candidate field and appropriately test key leadership behaviours and technical expertise for these flagship roles.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-12-05T14:42:13.587Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797697/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797697/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797697/answer","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797697/answer/previousversion/26969","Biography information for Greg Hands","202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-11-29","Trade Promotion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, pursuant to the Written Ministerial Statement of 27 November 2017 on trade matters,  HCWS271, what estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of appointing the nine Her Britannic Majesty's Trade Commissioners.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","116660"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797698","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-04","<p>Teams across the Department are working on delivering a successful EU exit. We have estimated an additional 450 staff requirement for officials over 2017-18 and are reviewing future resource needs.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-12-04T14:56:19.593Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797698/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797698/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797698/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-29","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate he has made of the (a) number of officials to be employed by his Department and (b) his Department's payroll in (i) 2018, (ii) 2019, (iii) 2020, (iv) 2021 and (v) 2022 as a result of the UK leaving EU.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","116661"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797699","Attorney General","false","2017-12-14","<p>Exit is an all-of-government operation. The Department for Exiting the European Union is doing detailed work with departments to prepare for the upcoming negotiations by understanding the risks and opportunities of leaving the EU and coordinating planning.</p><p>Members of staff across the Law Officers’ Departments provide advice and analysis on EU Exit issues as required. Given the interactions between EU exit work and the Departments’ other priorities, it would not be possible to give an accurate figure.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2017-12-14T15:03:12.473Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797699/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797699/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797699/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-11-29","Attorney General: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what estimate he has made of the (a) number of officials to be employed by his Department and (b) his Department's payroll in (i) 2018, (ii) 2019, (iii) 2020, (iv) 2021 and (v) 2022 as a result of the UK leaving EU.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","116662"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797700","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-12-07","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union is doing detailed work with departments to prepare for the upcoming negotiations by understanding the risks and opportunities of leaving the EU and coordinating planning. Staff within the EU and International Affairs Division lead on providing advice to Ministers on EU Exit and exit-related issues. Members of staff across the Department also provide advice and analysis on EU Exit issues as required. Given the interactions between EU exit work and the Department’s other priorities, it would not be possible to give an accurate figure for the information you have requested.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-12-07T15:55:43.367Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797700/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797700/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797700/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-29","Department for Work and Pensions: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the (a) number of officials to be employed by his Department and (b) his Department's payroll in (i) 2018, (ii) 2019, (iii) 2020, (iv) 2021 and (v) 2022 as a result of the UK leaving EU.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","116663"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797701","Cabinet Office","false","2017-12-07","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the reply given to the hon. Member for Tottenham on 24<sup>th</sup> October 2017, Official Report, C.106568.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-12-07T11:12:04.58Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797701/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797701/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797701/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-11-29","Cabinet Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of the (a) number of officials to be employed by his Department and (b) his Department's payroll in (i) 2018, (ii) 2019, (iii) 2020, (iv) 2021 and (v) 2022 as a result of the UK leaving EU.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","116664"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797702","Wales Office","false","2017-12-05","<p>EU Exit is an all-of-government operation. The Department for Exiting the European Union is doing detailed work with departments to prepare for the upcoming negotiations by understanding the risks and opportunities of leaving the EU and coordinating planning.</p><p> </p><p>Staff in the Office’s constitution and policy teams lead on providing advice to Ministers on EU Exit and exit-related issues. Members of staff across the department also provide advice and analysis on EU Exit issues as required.</p><p> </p><p>Given the interactions between EU exit work and the Office’s other priorities, it would not be possible to give an accurate figure.</p><p> </p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","116710","2017-12-05T11:22:21.127Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797702/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797702/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797702/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-11-29","Wales Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what estimate he has made of the (a) number of officials to be employed by his Department and (b) his Department's payroll in (i) 2018, (ii) 2019, (iii) 2020, (iv) 2021 and (v) 2022 as a result of the UK leaving EU.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","116665"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797703","HM Treasury","false","2017-12-07","<p>A significant proportion of the Treasury’s work is in some way related to exiting the European Union and this fluctuates over time as it interacts with Treasury’s other priorities.</p><p> </p><p>Many staff will work both on EU Exit and other priorities so it is not possible to accurately estimate the number of Treasury officials who will be engaged on EU Exit work at any one time.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","116479","2017-12-07T15:40:51.73Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797703/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797703/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797703/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-29","Treasury: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer,  what estimate he has made of the (a) number of officials to be employed by his Department and (b) his Department's payroll in (i) 2018, (ii) 2019, (iii) 2020, (iv) 2021 and (v) 2022 as a result of the UK leaving EU.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","116666"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797704","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-12-07","<p>Exit is an all-of-government operation. The Department for Exiting the European Union is doing detailed work with departments to prepare for the upcoming negotiations by understanding the risks and opportunities of leaving the EU and coordinating planning.</p><p>Staff within the EU exit team lead on providing advice to Ministers on EU Exit and exit-related issues. Members of staff across the Department also provide advice and analysis on EU Exit issues as required. Given the interactions between EU exit work and the Department’s other priorities, it would not be possible to give an accurate figure.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-12-07T17:58:29.86Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797704/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797704/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797704/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-29","Department for Communities and Local Government: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the (a) number of officials to be employed by his Department and (b) his Department's payroll in (i) 2018, (ii) 2019, (iii) 2020, (iv) 2021 and (v) 2022 as a result of the UK leaving EU.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","116667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797705","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-07","<p>Exit is an all-of-government operation. The Department for Exiting the European Union is doing detailed work with departments to prepare for the upcoming negotiations by understanding the risks and opportunities of leaving the EU and coordinating planning. Staff within the Department for Transport’s International and Regulatory Directorate lead on providing advice to Ministers on EU Exit and exit-related issues. Members of staff across the Department for Transport also provide advice and analysis on EU Exit issues as required. Given the interactions between EU exit work and the Department’s other priorities, it would not be possible to give an accurate figure.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-12-07T15:29:27.017Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797705/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797705/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797705/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-29","Department for Transport: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the (a) number of officials to be employed by his Department and (b) his Department's payroll in (i) 2018, (ii) 2019, (iii) 2020, (iv) 2021 and (v) 2022 as a result of the UK leaving EU.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","116668"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797706","Scotland Office","false","2017-12-05","<p>Exiting the European Union is an all-of-government operation for which the Department for Exiting the European Union is doing detailed work with departments to prepare for the upcoming negotiations by understanding the risks and opportunities of leaving the EU and coordinating planning.</p><p>Members of staff across the Department provide advice and analysis on EU Exit issues as required. Given the interactions between EU exit work and the Department’s other priorities, it would not be possible to give an accurate figure.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-12-05T11:11:47.317Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797706/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797706/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797706/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-11-29","Scotland Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what estimate he has made of the (a) number of officials to be employed by his Department and (b) his Department's payroll in (i) 2018, (ii) 2019, (iii) 2020, (iv) 2021 and (v) 2022 as a result of the UK leaving EU.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","116669"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797707","Department for Education","false","2017-12-07","<p>Exit is an all-of-government operation. The Department for Exiting the European Union is doing detailed work with departments to understand the risks and opportunities of leaving the EU and to coordinate planning. A team within the International Education Division leads on providing advice to ministers on EU Exit and exit-related issues. Members of staff across the Department for Education (DfE) provide advice and analysis on EU Exit issues across a range of DfE policy areas as required.</p><p> </p><p>Given the interactions between EU exit work and the department’s other priorities, it is not possible to give an accurate figure specifically for work on EU exit.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-12-07T17:32:39.287Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797707/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797707/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797707/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-29","Department for Education: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the (a) number of officials to be employed by her Department and (b) her Department's payroll in (i) 2018, (ii) 2019, (iii) 2020, (iv) 2021 and (v) 2022 as a result of the UK leaving EU.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","116670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797708","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-06","<p>Over 80% of Defra’s agenda is affected by the UK’s departure from the European Union. We continue to keep our resourcing plans under review, focusing both on recruitment and increasing the capability of new and existing staff.</p><p>Since June 2016, Defra has recruited over 550 additional staff to support our preparations for leaving the EU. The majority of these new staff are employed in the central department where they are working on a range of projects identified to enable a successful withdrawal from the EU.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","116466","2017-12-06T11:58:58.243Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797708/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797708/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797708/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-29","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate he has made of the (a) number of officials to be employed by his Department and (b) his Department's payroll in (i) 2018, (ii) 2019, (iii) 2020, (iv) 2021 and (v) 2022 as a result of the UK leaving EU.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","116671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797709","Cabinet Office","false","2017-12-21","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the reply given to the hon. Member for Tottenham on 24<sup>th</sup> October 2017, Official Report, C.106568.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-12-21T13:57:16.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797709/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797709/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797709/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-11-29","Prime Minister: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of the (a) number of officials to be employed by 10 Downing Street and (b) that office's payroll in (i) 2018, (ii) 2019, (iii) 2020, (iv) 2021 and (v) 2022 as a result of the UK leaving EU.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","116672"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797710","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-12-07","<p>All departments are equipping themselves with the resources they need to get the best deal for the UK. The Department for Exiting the European Union now has over 600 staff based in the UK plus the expertise of over 120 officials in Brussels. We regularly review headcount to ensure that we are appropriately staffed to deal with all aspects of the negotiations.</p><p>The Department is responsible for overseeing EU exit negotiations, as well as establishing the future relationship between the UK and EU. As such, all staff in the Department are dedicated to planning or supporting our work on EU exit.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker","116463","2017-12-07T16:50:05.733Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797710/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797710/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797710/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-11-29","Department for Exiting the European Union: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what estimate he has made of the (a) number of officials to be employed by his Department and (b) his Department's payroll in (i) 2018, (ii) 2019, (iii) 2020, (iv) 2021 and (v) 2022 as a result of the UK leaving EU.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","116673"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797711","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-12-07","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) keeps its staff numbers under regular review in response to Ministerial priorities. Furthermore, the FCO works closely with the Department for Exiting the European Union and other Government Departments to prepare for EU Exit. Staff within the FCO's Europe Directorate lead on providing advice to Ministers on EU Exit and exit-related issues. However, staff across the Department leading on other issues also provide advice and analysis as required. It is therefore not possible to give an accurate figure for the number of officials working on issues related to the UK leaving the EU, given the interactions between EU Exit work and the FCO's other priorities.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-12-07T17:08:47.66Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797711/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797711/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797711/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-29","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what estimate he has made of the (a) number of officials to be employed by his Department and (b) his Department's payroll in (i) 2018, (ii) 2019, (iii) 2020, (iv) 2021 and (v) 2022 as a result of the UK leaving EU.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","116674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797712","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-12-05","<p>EU exit affects a number of work areas across my Department and will therefore encompass a proportion of workload for many staff, the amount of which will vary over time.</p><p>The number of officials employed by my department is kept under regular review to ensure we have the appropriate resources to manage the departure from the EU.</p><p>Given the interactions between EU exit work and the Department’s other priorities, it would not be possible to give a year by year figure.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2017-12-05T17:44:23.313Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797712/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797712/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797712/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-11-29","Northern Ireland Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what estimate he has made of the (a) number of officials to be employed by his Department and (b) his Department's payroll in (i) 2018, (ii) 2019, (iii) 2020, (iv) 2021 and (v) 2022 as a result of the UK leaving EU.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","116675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797713","Women and Equalities","false","2017-12-07","<p>Exit is an all-of-government operation. The Department for Exiting the European Union is doing detailed work with departments to understand the risks and opportunities of leaving the EU and to coordinate planning. A team within the Government Equalities Office (GEO) leads on providing advice to ministers on EU Exit and exit-related issues. Members of GEO staff provide advice and analysis on EU Exit issues across a range of policy areas affecting women and equalities, as required.</p><p> </p><p>Given the interactions between EU exit work and GEO’s other priorities, it is not possible to give an accurate figure specifically for work on EU exit.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-12-07T17:44:57.687Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797713/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797713/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797713/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-11-29","Government Equalities Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what estimate she has made of the (a) number of officials to be employed by her Department and (b) her Department's payroll in (i) 2018, (ii) 2019, (iii) 2020, (iv) 2021 and (v) 2022 as a result of the UK leaving EU.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","116676"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797714","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-12-06","<p>As with all government departments, members of staff across the MoJ provide advice and analysis on EU Exit issues as required. Given the interactions between EU Exit work and the MoJ’s other priorities, it is not possible to provide an estimate of the number of officials to be employed for these financial years</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-12-06T12:46:15.94Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797714/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797714/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797714/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-29","Ministry of Justice: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate he has made of the (a) number of officials to be employed by his Department and (b) his Department's payroll in (i) 2018, (ii) 2019, (iii) 2020, (iv) 2021 and (v) 2022 as a result of the UK leaving EU.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","116677"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797715","Department of Health","false","2017-12-07","<p>Leaving the European Union is an all-of-Government operation. The Department for Exiting the European Union is doing detailed work with departments to prepare for the upcoming negotiations by understanding the risks and opportunities of leaving the EU and coordinating planning.</p><p> </p><p>Staff within the Global and Public Health Directorate of this Department lead on providing advice to Ministers on EU Exit and exit-related issues.</p><p> </p><p>Members of staff across the Department also provide advice and analysis on EU Exit issues as required.</p><p> </p><p>Given the interactions between EU exit work and the Department’s other priorities, it would not be possible to give an accurate figure.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","116469","2017-12-07T14:26:48.993Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797715/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797715/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797715/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-29","Department of Health: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the (a) number of officials to be employed by his Department and (b) his Department's payroll in (i) 2018, (ii) 2019, (iii) 2020, (iv) 2021 and (v) 2022 as a result of the UK leaving EU.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","116678"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797716","Department for International Trade","false","2017-12-07","<p>Leaving the European Union is an all-of-government operation. The Department for Exiting the European Union is doing detailed work with departments to prepare for the upcoming negotiations by understanding the risks and opportunities of leaving the EU and coordinating planning.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for International Trade was established to secure UK and global prosperity by promoting and financing international trade and investment and championing free trade.</p><p> </p><p>Given the interactions between EU exit work and the Department’s other priorities, it would not be possible to give a specific figure.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-12-07T14:27:26.367Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797716/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797716/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797716/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-11-29","Department for International Trade: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what estimate he has made of the (a) number of officials to be employed by his Department and (b) his Department's payroll in (i) 2018, (ii) 2019, (iii) 2020, (iv) 2021 and (v) 2022 as a result of the UK leaving EU.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","116679"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797717","Home Office","false","2017-12-04","<p>The Home Office constantly monitors the capabilities it needs to deliver the Government’s agenda. With EU exit negotiations underway, we continue to assess how this, alongside our other priorities, will impact on the workforce and capabilities required. Any resulting changes to resource requirements will be factored into strategic planning.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-12-04T17:42:14.56Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797717/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797717/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797717/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-29","Home Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the (a) number of officials to be employed by her Department and (b) her Department's payroll in (i) 2018, (ii) 2019, (iii) 2020, (iv) 2021 and (v) 2022 as a result of the UK leaving EU.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","116680"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797718","Department for International Development","false","2017-12-06","<p>EU Exit is an all-of-government operation. The Department for International Development is doing detailed work with departments to prepare for the upcoming negotiations by understanding the risks and opportunities of leaving the EU and coordinating planning.</p><p> </p><p>Staff within the Europe and Trade for Development teams lead on providing advice to Ministers on EU Exit and exit-related issues. Members of staff across the Department also provide advice and analysis on EU Exit issues as required.</p><p> </p><p>Given the interactions between EU exit work and the Department’s other priorities, it would not be possible to give an accurate figure.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-12-06T12:22:43.337Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797718/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797718/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797718/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-11-29","Department for International Development: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what estimate she has made of the (a) number of officials to be employed by her Department and (b) her Department's payroll in (i) 2018, (ii) 2019, (iii) 2020, (iv) 2021 and (v) 2022 as a result of the UK leaving EU.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","116681"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797719","Department for International Development","false","2017-12-06","<p>The UK is the largest donor to Gavi, the global vaccine alliance that provides developing countries with pneumococcol to vaccinate against pneumonia. 109 million children were vaccinated between 2010 and 2016, thanks to Gavi’s support, saving an estimated 762,000 lives.</p><p>DFID supports Gavi’s Pneumococcol Advanced Market commitment which reduces costs, enabling 58 countries to introduce vaccinations. We also support countries to build stronger health systems that can respond to existing disease burdens and emerging health issues, including pneumonia.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-12-06T16:11:26.363Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797719/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797719/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797719/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-11-29","Developing Countries: Pneumonia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps she is taking to prevent deaths from pneumonia in developing countries in children under five years old; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","116682"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797720","Department for International Development","false","2017-12-06","<p>The UK Government has committed to saving 1.4 million children’s lives by immunising 76 million children against killer diseases by 2020. Through The Ross Fund we are leading a major new global research programme. This will accelerate the development of vaccines and drugs to eliminate some of the world’s deadliest infectious diseases, as well as saving lives from malaria and TB.</p><p>DFID supports countries to build stronger health systems, which will be able to respond to the existing disease burden and emerging health issues.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-12-06T16:15:09.84Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797720/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797720/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/797720/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-11-29","Developing Countries: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what progress is being made in ending preventable child deaths by 2030 as set out in the UN Sustainable Development Goals.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","116683"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800731","Women and Equalities","false","2017-12-08","<p>The Employment Tribunal Service case management system does not collect or hold the level of detail of information requested, which could only be obtained from the paper records of each tribunal office.</p><p> </p><p>People with HIV are automatically considered disabled for the purposes of the Equality Act 2010 and afforded all the relevant protections under its provisions, which make it unlawful to discriminate against people because of a disability in matters of employment, education and the provision of goods and services.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-12-08T14:16:42.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800731/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800731/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/800731/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-11-29","Employment: HIV Infection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, how many cases of HIV-related workplace discrimination have been reported, in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Rosie Duffield","Canterbury","Rosie Duffield","117352"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795433","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-04","<p>The Government’s Cycle to Work scheme allows employers to loan bicycle and bicycle safety equipment to employees as a tax-free benefit. The Department has produced guidelines to encourage employers to take advantage of this scheme.</p><p>The Government’s Cycling and Walking Investment Strategy, published in April 2017, sets out the other steps the Government is taking to support cycling, and the funding available to improve local cycling provisions, provide safer cycle routes and increase cycle parking facilities.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","115856","2017-12-04T15:26:50.11Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795433/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795433/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795433/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-28","Cycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what further steps are being taken to assist employers in encouraging employees to cycle to work.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","115854"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795648","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-28","<p>I refer the hon member to my oral answer of earlier today to the hon member for Midlothian (Danielle Rowley).</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-11-28T14:35:39.103Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795648/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795648/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795648/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-28","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","What discussions he has had with Secretary of State for Work and Pensions on the potential effect of the roll-out of universal credit on levels of household income?","false","Biography information for Fiona Onasanya","Peterborough","Fiona Onasanya","902584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795651","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-30","<p>The Department’s Transport Investment Strategy makes clear that we can and must seek to enhance our global competitiveness by making Britain a more attractive place to trade and invest. There are a number of initiatives in this area, including:</p><p> </p><ul><li>A Port Connectivity Study that is considering the levels of current road and rail access to our ports. Effective links to ports are a fundamental part of a successful supply chain;</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>The Clean Growth Strategy is examining cost-effective options TO shift more freight from road to rail; and</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>The Department will be working closely with the National Infrastructure Commission as it examines the UK’s freight sector and new measures by which Government can help businesses transport their goods faster and more efficiently.</li></ul><p><strong> </strong></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-11-30T13:44:05.24Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795651/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795651/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795651/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-28","Transport: Infrastructure","1","House of Commons","What discussions he has had with the President of the Board of Trade on the potential merits for future UK trade of better integrating road and rail infrastructure.","false","Biography information for Mr Ranil Jayawardena","North East Hampshire","Mr Ranil Jayawardena","902676"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795669","Cabinet Office","false","2017-12-11","<p>The last three years have been a unique period in UK politics, with General Elections in 2015 and 2017 and the EU Referendum in 2016 all raising public awareness in the electoral system. This has led, in turn, to an increase in the size of the electoral register to a record high of nearly 47 million.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-12-11T16:35:08.813Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795669/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795669/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795669/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-11-28","Electorate","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made on the effects of party political activity on (a) electoral registration and (b) voter engagement in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","116023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795670","Department of Health","false","2017-12-06","<p>In 2017/18 the Department has provided Skills for Care with funding of £22.3 million to deliver the Department’s adult social care workforce priorities including the recruitment and retention of domicilliary care workers.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-12-06T13:10:21.183Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795670/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795670/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795670/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-28","Home Care Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will earmark funding to support the recruitment and retention of carers who provide personal homecare visits.","false","Biography information for Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","Tooting","Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","116024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795671","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-12-01","<p>Many working age people are unprepared for the significant financial impact immediately following a bereavement. Thus Bereavement Support Payment is intended to provide short-term financial support for a bereaved spouse or civil partner following premature death during working life. This is a long-standing position in bereavement benefits which the Government has no plans to change.</p><p><em></em></p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-12-01T16:58:27.02Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795671/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795671/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795671/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-28","Pensioners: Bereavement Support Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will extend Bereavement Support Payments to people above the state pension age.","false","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden","116025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795672","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-12-06","<p>My Department welcome's the work carried out by Crisis. We have committed £20 million funding to improve access to the private rented sector for those who are, or are at risk of, homelessness or rough sleeping, and are currently considering how best to use this.</p><p>This comes on top of £28 million funding for 3 regional Housing First pilot schemes which will offer permanent homes to homeless people.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-12-06T17:49:10.043Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795672/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795672/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795672/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-28","Private Rented Housing: Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment his Department has made of the potential merits of introducing projects on Help to Rent and on a national rent deposit guarantee proposed by Crisis in its report, Crisis Help to Rent programmes.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","116026"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795673","Department of Health","false","2017-12-06","<p>There are currently 2,000 Nursing Associates in training within 35 Health Education England Pilots, due to complete and become qualified in 2019. Nursing Associates spend 675 hours on placement at locations external to their employed place of work, where they gain a wide range of experience caring for people at all stages of life, across nursing fields and in other care settings, including in hospital, in the community and in a person’s home.</p><p> </p><p>Nursing Associates are an England only role. National Health Service staffing in Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales is a matter for each of the devolved administrations.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-12-06T12:21:59.44Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795673/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795673/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795673/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-28","Nursing Associates: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of training time for the new nursing associate role is allocated to each specialism.","true","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","116027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795674","Department for Education","false","2017-12-01","<p>Autumn Budget announced £177 million investment in maths over the next 5 years. The budgeted amounts for each of the specified programmes are as follows:</p><p> </p><p>- £27 million to further expand the Teaching for Mastery maths programme to reach 11,000 primary and secondary schools by 2022-23;</p><p>- £83.2 million to provide £600 for every additional pupil taking Maths or Further Maths A levels or Core Maths;</p><p>- £18 million additional funding for specialist Maths Schools;</p><p>- £8.5 million for the post-16 basic Maths pilot, which will run for 2 years; and</p><p>- £40.3 million for Further Education Centres of Excellence.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>£ million</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2018-19</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2019-20</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2020-21</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2021-22</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2022-23</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>TOTAL</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>a) Teaching for mastery of mathematics</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>27</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>b) Maths premium for 16-19 year olds</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>4.6</p></td><td><p>15</p></td><td><p>26.6</p></td><td><p>37</p></td><td><p>83.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>c) Maths schools</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>18</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>d) Post-16 basic Maths pilot</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>4.3</p></td><td><p>4.2</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>8.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>e) FE Centres of Excellence</p></td><td><p>7.2</p></td><td><p>6.5</p></td><td><p>8.5</p></td><td><p>8.9</p></td><td><p>9.2</p></td><td><p>40.3</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>These figures do not include the Barnett consequential for these measures, which is provided to the Devolved Administrations.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Education's total budgets in 2020-21 and beyond will be set at a future Spending Review, but will include the full costs of these Budget measures.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-12-01T14:32:24.587Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795674/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795674/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795674/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-28","Mathematics: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to paragraph 4.24 of Autumn Budget 2017, what funding her Department plans to allocate for (a) expanding the Teaching for Mastery maths programme, (b) the premium for pupils taking maths, further maths or core maths, (c) providing an annual £350,000 for every maths school under the specialist maths school model, (d) the pilot to improve GCSE maths resit outcomes and (e) establishing Further Education Centres of Excellence in each of the next five financial years.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","116028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795675","Department for Education","false","2017-12-01","<p>£100 million of funding from the soft drinks industry levy in 2018-19 will be provided for the healthy pupils’ capital fund. This funding will be made available to improve school facilities to support a range of healthy pupils activities, including PE and sports, after school activities and healthy eating.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-12-01T12:46:13.317Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795675/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795675/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795675/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-28","Extracurricular Activities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what additional funding her Department has made available or plans to make available to secondary schools to increase the range of activities offered to pupils outside the school day; and whether any funding was provided for that purpose from the soft drinks industry levy.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","116029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795676","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-12-06","<p>The broadband project, supported by UK taxpayer funding and delivered by Digital Scotland Superfast Broadband, had provided superfast broadband coverage to approximately 520,000 premises by the end of September 2017. The Scottish Government has been funded a further £20 Milllion in 2014 to connect more Scottish households, but has failed even to open procurement. Over 7% of Scottish premises still have no access to Superfast broadband.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-12-06T14:21:49.29Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795676/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795676/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795676/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-28","Broadband: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate he has made of the number of proportion of premises which have access to fibre and superfast broadband as a result of the implementation of the Digital Scotland Superfast Broadband programme.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","116030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795677","HM Treasury","false","2017-12-05","<p>I refer the Hon Member to my written answer of 5 July 2017 (UIN 1465).</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-12-05T15:58:45.853Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795677/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795677/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795677/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-28","Employee Benefit Trusts: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will undertake a review the regulation of employee benefit trusts following representations made on behalf of the Roadchef Employees Benefit Trust.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","116031"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795678","Department of Health","false","2017-12-05","<p>The Food Standards Agency (FSA) considers that the mandatory display of food hygiene ratings in England would be beneficial and is using the evidence from Wales and Northern Ireland to build a strong case. The FSA is exploring how a statutory scheme could be delivered in England, including display of ratings on online food ordering platforms, as part of their work to deliver a new model of regulation for food businesses – the Regulating Our Future programme, which is expected to have changes to the regulatory system in place by 2020.</p><p> </p><p>The Regulating Our Future programme is redesigning how food businesses are regulated for food safety, and as hygiene ratings are currently based on local authority inspections of food businesses it is important that the Food Hygiene Rating Scheme (FHRS) is part of those considerations. Embedding FHRS into the future model of food regulation will ensure we have a robust and credible scheme that continues to deliver benefits for consumers</p><p> </p><p>As a result of further regulation under the statutory scheme in Northern Ireland, it is anticipated that next year businesses which offer on-line ordering of food will need to publish their ratings online so that they can be seen before an order is placed. Wales is also considering introducing further regulations to require the promotion of food hygiene ratings on food businesses’ websites.</p><p> </p><p>The FSA remains committed to the successful and trusted FHRS. The FSA will continue to ensure the FHRS is sustainable and work towards the introduction of a statutory scheme that would require mandatory display of ratings in England as is the case in Wales and Northern Ireland. The Government will consider the case carefully once it is available.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","115995 ; 115999","2017-12-05T16:40:29.063Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795678/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795678/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795678/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-28","Food: Hygiene","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what evidence his Department has received from the Food Standards Agency on the effect on public health of the mandatory display of hygiene scores at food outlets in Wales.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","116032"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795679","HM Treasury","false","2017-12-01","Information on the number of disabled children eligible for Tax-Free Childcare is not available.<p> </p>The response to PQ 106926 provided the number of children for whom there was a live Tax-Free Childcare account. The Office for Budget Responsibility’s Fiscal Outlook 2017 provided details of the number of parents who had made a payment from their Tax-Free Childcare account.","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","116221","2017-12-01T13:09:47.877Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795679/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795679/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795679/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-28","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 27 November 2017 to Question 115078, what estimate he has made of the number of disabled children eligible for a tax-free childcare account.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","116033"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795680","Cabinet Office","false","2017-12-07","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-12-07T10:36:01.147Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795680/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795680/answer","PQ116034.pdf","PQ116034.pdf","UKSA response","UKSA response","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795680/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-11-28","Public Sector: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister of the Cabinet Office what the total number of Northern Irish workers currently employed by the public sector across the rest of the UK is.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","116034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795682","HM Treasury","false","2017-12-01","The Soft Drinks Industry Levy applies across England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland. In England, the new levy revenue will be invested in giving school-aged children a brighter and healthier future. The Barnett formula will apply to this spending in the normal way, and it will be for the Devolved Administrations to choose how they allocate this funding.<p> </p><p>As a result of funding allocated for these purposes to the Department for Education at Budget 2016, the Scottish Government, Welsh Government and a Northern Ireland Executive will receive £36.7m, £21.2m and £12.3m respectively in 2018/19.</p><p> </p><p>Subsequent changes to the levy-funded spending package in England have had no impact on these allocations.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-12-01T13:05:56.743Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795682/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795682/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795682/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-28","Soft Drinks: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much of the revenue raised from the soft drinks industry levy will go to (a) Scotland, (b) Wales, and (c) Northern Ireland as a consequence of the Barnett Formula in the next financial year.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","116036"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795683","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-01","<p>We continue to develop plans for a lorry park, and approximately £12 million has been spent on developing the lorry area at Stanford West. This figure includes costs which will be reused as part of the development of the permanent solution announced on 15 November. It also includes the costs of purchasing some properties adjoining the site, which may be resold in due course, reducing the overall cost of the project.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-12-01T12:30:45.303Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795683/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795683/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795683/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-28","Large Goods Vehicles: Stanford West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much has been spent on the planned lorry holding park in Stanford West in Kent.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","116037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795684","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-01","<p>In the 2016 to 2017 financial year, the Department for Transport spent almost £3.5m on supporting the not-for-profit community transport sector through the Bus Service Operator’s Grant (BSOG), with a further £2m through the second round of Community Minibus Fund. In the current financial year we predict that support to community transport operators through BSOG will again be approximately £3.5m. The Department has also announced an additional £250,000 to support community transport organisations with PSV Operator licence requirements.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-12-01T12:28:13.837Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795684/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795684/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795684/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-28","Community Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to expand and support the not-for-profit community transport sector.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","116038"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795685","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-06","<p>The Department for Transport recognises the important role which both commercial and not-for-profit operators play in providing vital services to communities. We have no plans to reform the bus industry to expand not-for-profit services on commercial routes.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-12-06T16:29:32.527Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795685/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795685/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795685/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-28","Bus Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to reform the bus industry to expand not-for-profit services on commercial routes.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","116039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795686","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-06","<p>The government will work with industry to extend the benefits of discounted rail travel to ensure those aged 16 to 30 can access appropriate concessions. This will include the introduction of a new railcard for ages 26 to 30, which the government anticipates will increase the number of journeys taken. Further details will be announced in agreement with the rail industry in due course.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-12-06T16:33:31.553Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795686/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795686/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795686/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-28","Railways: Concessions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the cost will be of his proposed policy on the railcard for ages 26 to 30 years; how that policy proposal will be funded; and when he plans to introduce that railcard on all franchises.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","116040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795687","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-06","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office is the lead department for discussions with the UK Overseas Territories on these issues.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-12-06T11:35:57.303Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795687/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795687/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795687/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-28","Marine Protected Areas: British Overseas Territories","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his counterparts in the Governments of UK Overseas Territories on creating fully enforced Marine Protected Areas in their waters.","false","Biography information for Tonia Antoniazzi","Gower","Tonia Antoniazzi","116041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795688","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-12-01","<p>There are no plans to pause the rollout of Universal Credit. We have, however, carefully revised the rollout plan to ensure we continue safely and gradually to rollout this important welfare reform. This will mean a slight change in date for when Universal Credit Full Service will be rolled out in some Jobcentres.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-12-01T12:55:20.85Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795688/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795688/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795688/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-28","Universal Credit: Cardiff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, for what reasons the rollout of universal credit is not being delayed in Cardiff.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","116042"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795689","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-12-01","<p>My Department is planning to undertake a public consultation before the launch of the Shared Prosperity Fund.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2017-12-01T13:22:33.793Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795689/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795689/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795689/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-28","EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether the Government plans to undertake a public consultation before the launch of the Shared Prosperity Fund.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","116043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795690","Wales Office","false","2017-12-01","<p>Historically West Wales and the Valleys, as one of the most disadvantaged areas in Europe, has been a net recipient of European Structural and Investment Funding, as has Wales as a whole. The UK’s exit from the European Union provides us with the opportunity to consider how funding for growth across the UK is designed and how we can deliver the best outcomes for the people of Wales.</p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-12-01T10:20:29.413Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795690/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795690/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795690/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-11-28","EU Grants and Loans: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what his policy is on the status of West Wales and the Valleys under the Governments new Shared Prosperity Fund; and if he will consider that area's status as eligible to receive the highest level of support under European Structural Funds when allocating funds under that policy.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","116044"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795691","HM Treasury","false","2017-12-01","<p>The potential cost of the Government’s guarantee of EU projects in Wales will be subject to a number of factors. These include the outcome of the negotiations and the outcome of bids made directly to the Commission. Departments and devolved administrations are focusing on ensuring the guarantee will be administered if necessary.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-12-01T13:14:24.91Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795691/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795691/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795691/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-28","EU Grants and Loans: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the cost of underwriting EU projects in Wales that extend beyond the UK's period of membership of the EU.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","116045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795692","Wales Office","false","2017-12-01","<p>I hold regular discussions with Cabinet Secretaries in the Welsh Government to discuss a range of issues, including the impact on Wales of the UK leaving the European Union.</p><p> </p><p>Our manifesto committed to creating the UK Shared Prosperity Fund and work is ongoing across Government to consider how best this can be achieved. As per our commitment, we will of course work with the Welsh Government and other stakeholders across Wales and the UK.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-12-01T10:21:30.12Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795692/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795692/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795692/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-11-28","EU Grants and Loans: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, whether he has had any meetings with the Welsh Government on the future operation of the Shared Prosperity Fund.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","116046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795693","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2017-12-01","<p>Since the referendum my department has undertaken a wide range of qualitative and quantitative analysis across all sectors of the economy. However, the Secretary of State and I have made consistently clear that our analysis does not exist in the form of Impact Assessments.</p><p>Following the motion on 1 November, my department began collating our analysis into an accessible and informative set of reports for the Exiting the European Union Committee and the European Union Committee in the House of Lords. This has been a very substantial undertaking.</p><p>Cabinet Committee clearance was given on Monday 27 November and the reports were delivered immediately to the Committees. These sectoral analyses are being made available in reading rooms for all colleagues to access.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-12-01T15:00:31.433Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795693/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795693/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795693/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2017-11-28","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, when he (a) ordered the drawing up of and (b) received the completed Brexit impact assessments.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","116047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795694","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-12-01","<p>The aim of Permanent Structured Cooperation (PESCO) is to strengthen EU Member States' cooperation in military matters. PESCO is voluntary and works on an opt-in basis.</p><p>The UK Government has not committed to PESCO but supports its ambition to develop military capabilities that address the shortfalls in EU and NATO contexts. We welcome PESCO as a tool to support the development of capabilities that Europe needs for its security, provided it remains complementary to NATO and encourages EU-NATO cooperation; and that projects carried out under PESCO remain Member State-owned and the capabilities delivered are available not only to the EU but can also be used in support of NATO and UN operations.</p><p>There are no associated working groups but UK officials from the Foreign and Commonwealth Office and Ministry of Defence have attended PESCO workshops at both the technical and policy level.</p><p>We are encouraging Member States to develop PESCO to be open to third country participation where there is clear value in doing so.</p><p>Our vision is of a unique third country partnership that enables unprecedented levels of practical cooperation in tackling common threats building on our shared values and interests. We believe that PESCO must be designed in a way that promotes an open and competitive European Defence industry.</p><p>Our approach reflects our commitment to European defence and security, and protecting the interests of UK industry.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-12-01T14:54:11.287Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795694/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795694/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795694/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-28","EU Defence Policy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what relationship the Government plans to have with the EU's Permanent Structured Cooperation, known as PESCO, after leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","116048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795695","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-12-01","<p>The Prime Minister recently announced an additional £2 billion funding for affordable housing, including for social rent homes in areas of high affordability pressure. This has increased the Government’s Affordable Housing Programme 2016-21 budget to more than £9 billion and will deliver tens of thousands of new homes.</p><p>As the funding for social rent will be focused on areas with acute affordability challenges, the amount of funding given out will be dependent on the bids received.</p><p>My Department is also working on a social housing green paper that will consider the wider issues facing the sector.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","116050","2017-12-01T14:10:29.953Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795695/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795695/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795695/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-28","Social Rented Housing: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to Autumn Budget 2017, how much funding has been allocated for the provision of new social housing.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","116049"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795696","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-12-01","<p>The Prime Minister recently announced an additional £2 billion funding for affordable housing, including for social rent homes in areas of high affordability pressure. This has increased the Government’s Affordable Housing Programme 2016-21 budget to more than £9 billion and will deliver tens of thousands of new homes.</p><p>As the funding for social rent will be focused on areas with acute affordability challenges, the amount of funding given out will be dependent on the bids received.</p><p>My Department is also working on a social housing green paper that will consider the wider issues facing the sector.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","116049","2017-12-01T14:10:29.907Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795696/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795696/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795696/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-28","Social Rented Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to the Autumn Budget 2017, how many more social housing units will be built in each of the next three years.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","116050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795697","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-12-07","<p>36 local authorities have been in touch with my Department regarding work to ensure fire safety in tower blocks.</p><p>My Department has asked nine local authorities to provide more detailed information about the support they require for essential works. Two of these local authorities have provided this detailed information so far. My officials are working with them on their requests to assess what support we might provide.</p><p>My Department has asked the remaining 25 local authorities to contact us again if they consider a building to be unsafe, once they have deemed what measures are essential to make the building fire-safe. This should be based on expert advice and take into account any recommendations or advice from the local fire and rescue service.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-12-07T17:33:03.717Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795697/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795697/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795697/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-28","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, which local authorities have received a) extra borrowing approval and b) the ability to transfer money from the general fund in order to carry out fire safety work on tower blocks.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","116051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795698","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-01","<p>Onshore wind is an established (Group 1) technology for the purposes of the Contracts for Difference (CfD) scheme. No decisions have been taken on running an allocation round for these technologies but if one was run, onshore wind projects in Scotland would be eligible to apply.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is seeking state aid approval to classify remote island wind as a separate technology in Group 2 of the CfD scheme. This could include some onshore wind projects proposed for the remote islands of Scotland, including in Orkney, Shetland and the Western Isles. The Clean Growth Strategy announced that we would provide up to £557m in total of annual funding for Group 2 technologies.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-12-01T13:30:38.997Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795698/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795698/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795698/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-28","Wind Power: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when his Department plans to announce voluntary Contracts for Difference auctions for on shore wind in Scotland; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","116052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795699","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-05","<p>The Government’s Clean Growth Strategy, published on 12 October 2017, commits Government to working with ongoing initiatives in Teesside, Merseyside, South Wales and Grangemouth to test the potential for development of carbon capture usage and storage (CCUS) industrial decarbonisation clusters.</p><p> </p><p>The Department met with Scottish Government, The Crown Estate Scotland, Pale Blue Dot Energy Ltd, Scottish Carbon Capture &amp; Storage and Summit Power on 15 November 2017 to discuss CCUS in Scotland and these discussions continue.</p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-12-05T11:24:02.46Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795699/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795699/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795699/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-28","Carbon Capture and Storage: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of the steps needed to develop a carbon capture and storage cluster in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","116053"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795700","Department of Health","false","2017-12-05","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answers I gave on 29 November 2017 to Questions <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=114827" target="_blank">114827</a>, <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=114828+" target="_blank">114828 </a>and <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=114836" target="_blank">114836</a>.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","116016 ; 116018","2017-12-05T14:29:52.683Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795700/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795700/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795700/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-28","Pregnancy: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that women who know they are expecting a child with disability have access to accurate information about the experiences of families who have raised a child with disability.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","116054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795701","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-06","<p>The Bus Services Act 2017 incorporates powers to introduce an Accessible Information Requirement, mandating the provision of audible and visible information on local bus services in Great Britain.</p><p>We are currently working with stakeholders to develop the detail of the requirement, including timescales for its implementation, with a view to consulting publicly in 2018. Following consideration of the consultation responses, we expect to publish Regulations and accompanying guidance when the Parliamentary timetable permits.</p><p /><p />","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-12-06T16:27:19.45Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795701/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795701/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795701/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-28","Bus Services: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the Bus Services Act 2017, when he plans to issue the guidance and regulations on audio-visual next stop announcements.","false","Biography information for Iain Stewart","Milton Keynes South","Iain Stewart","116055"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795702","HM Treasury","false","2017-12-11","<p>The like for like replacement of the nuclear submarine fleet is at the heart of the most recent SDSR and the funding settlement that accompanied it at SR15.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has no plans to transfer the costs of upgrading or replacing the UK's nuclear deterrent from the Ministry of Defence to another Government accounting department at this time.</p><p> </p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-12-11T13:53:39.417Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795702/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795702/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795702/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-28","Trident","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an assessment of the effect of transferring the costs of upgrading or replacing the UK's nuclear deterrent from the Ministry of Defence to another Government accounting department; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Iain Stewart","Milton Keynes South","Iain Stewart","116056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795703","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-05","<p>The Department commissioned Pale Blue Dot Energy Ltd to undertake a study ‘CO<sub>2</sub> transport and storage: Review of business models (Phase 1)’. This work has now been completed and the report will be published on gov.uk in January 2018.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-12-05T16:16:12.29Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795703/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795703/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795703/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-28","Carbon Capture and Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, with reference to the contract awarded in February 2017 to Pale Blue Dot to review business models for carbon dioxide transport and storage, whether this work has been completed.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","116057"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795704","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-12-06","<p>As part of our work on the Digital Charter announced in the Queen's speech, the Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport published an Internet Safety Strategy on 11 October which focuses on keeping all users safe online. The Strategy covers the responsibilities of companies to their users, the use of technical solutions to prevent online harms and Government's role in supporting users. The Strategy includes proposals to tackle cyberbullying.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","116059 ; 116060","2017-12-06T10:37:38.673Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795704/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795704/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795704/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-28","Social Media: Bullying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what steps she is taking to protect adults from cyber-bullying on social media.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","116058"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795705","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-12-06","<p>As part of our work on the Digital Charter announced in the Queen's speech, the Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport published an Internet Safety Strategy on 11 October which focuses on keeping all users safe online. The Strategy covers the responsibilities of companies to their users, the use of technical solutions to prevent online harms and Government's role in supporting users. The Strategy includes proposals to tackle cyberbullying.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","116058 ; 116060","2017-12-06T10:37:38.737Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795705/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795705/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795705/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-28","Social Media: Bullying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what steps she is taking to protect children from cyber-bullying on social media.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","116059"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795706","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-12-06","<p>As part of our work on the Digital Charter announced in the Queen's speech, the Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport published an Internet Safety Strategy on 11 October which focuses on keeping all users safe online. The Strategy covers the responsibilities of companies to their users, the use of technical solutions to prevent online harms and Government's role in supporting users. The Strategy includes proposals to tackle cyberbullying.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","116058 ; 116059","2017-12-06T10:37:38.783Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795706/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795706/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795706/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-28","Social Media: Bullying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what the Government’s policy is on the responsibilities of social media companies relating to cyber-bullying; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","116060"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795707","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-12-06","<p>Ministers and officials have regular meetings and discussions with social media companies on a range of issues including cyber bullying. Details of ministerial meetings are published quarterly on the Gov.uk website.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-12-06T10:41:12.173Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795707/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795707/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795707/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-28","Social Media: Bullying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether she has had meetings with social media companies to discuss their responsibilities relating to cyber-bullying in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","116061"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795708","Department of Health","false","2017-12-06","<p>Since the full implementation of the Tobacco and Related Products Regulations in May 2017, the Department has received a number of representations on different aspects of the legislation, including on the use of images on packaging; the regulation of e-cigarettes; and the regulation of chewing tobacco.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-12-06T12:35:08.09Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795708/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795708/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795708/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-28","Tobacco","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent representations he has received on the implementation of the Tobacco and Related Products Regulations; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","116062"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795709","Department of Health","false","2017-12-06","<p>The Chartered Trading Standards Institute, commissioned by the Department, undertakes an annual survey to assess tobacco control activities carried out by councils across England, including relating to compliance with the Tobacco and Related Products Regulations 2016. Further detail about the levels of non-compliance and associated prosecutions can be found in the 2016/17 Tobacco Control Survey, published on the Trading Standards website.</p><p> </p><p>Throughout 2015/16, the Department, supported by the Chartered Trading Standards Institute, has delivered a comprehensive training package across nine English regions. This consisted of both face to face learning events as well as e-learning opportunities to support the implementation of the Tobacco Products Directive and the Standardised Packaging of Tobacco Products Regulations 2015.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","116064","2017-12-06T17:22:47.523Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795709/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795709/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795709/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-28","Tobacco","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what information his Department holds on a) levels of non-compliance with the Tobacco and Related Products Regulations and b) the number of successful prosecutions for non-compliance in the last year for which figures are available; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","116063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795710","Department of Health","false","2017-12-06","<p>The Chartered Trading Standards Institute, commissioned by the Department, undertakes an annual survey to assess tobacco control activities carried out by councils across England, including relating to compliance with the Tobacco and Related Products Regulations 2016. Further detail about the levels of non-compliance and associated prosecutions can be found in the 2016/17 Tobacco Control Survey, published on the Trading Standards website.</p><p> </p><p>Throughout 2015/16, the Department, supported by the Chartered Trading Standards Institute, has delivered a comprehensive training package across nine English regions. This consisted of both face to face learning events as well as e-learning opportunities to support the implementation of the Tobacco Products Directive and the Standardised Packaging of Tobacco Products Regulations 2015.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","116063","2017-12-06T17:22:47.587Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795710/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795710/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795710/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-28","Tobacco: Trading Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what training is provided by his Department to local authority trading standards officers on the Tobacco and Related Products Regulations; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","116064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795711","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-12-01","<p>Details of broadband speeds are published by Ofcom and available here: <a href="https://www.ofcom.org.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0015/100761/UK-home-broadband-performance,-November-2016-Technical-report.pdf" target="_blank"><em>https://www.ofcom.org.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0015/100761/UK-home-broadband-performance,-November-2016-Technical-report.pdf</em></a></p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-12-01T12:07:41.007Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795711/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795711/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795711/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-28","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what her most recent estimate is of the average (a) advertised speed for broadband services, (b) speed received by consumers for broadband services; and if she will make a statement","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","116065"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795712","Department for Education","false","2017-12-01","<p>We have developed the Active Lives: Children and Young People survey (ALC), to provide a world-leading approach to gathering data on how children engage with sport and physical activity. Each term, a number of schools will be selected randomly to take part in the survey, with the aim of getting 100,000 children and young people in Years 1 to 11 to complete it each academic year. The survey will include measures of children’s activity levels, physical literacy, wellbeing, self-efficacy and levels of social trust.</p><p>The first set of baseline results will be available from early 2019, and will give us a better, and more joined-up, understanding of children’s engagement in sport and physical activity through their early lives and into adulthood.</p><p> </p><p>The Department of Education has not collected data on time spent participating in sport or physical activity by pupils in primary schools prior to the establishment of the Active Lives Children Survey.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-12-01T12:48:48.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795712/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795712/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795712/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-28","Sports: Primary Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the average number of hours of sport and physical activity undertaken by pupils in primary schools in England in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","116066"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795713","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-04","<p>The Nuclear Skills Strategy Group conducts, as part of its activities, a labour market intelligence gathering exercise across the sector to produce an annual Nuclear Workforce Assessment (NWA), which identifies the sector’s forward demand requirements. However, the first NWA report was published in 2014, with a subsequent iteration released in 2015, to improve the estimates for job figures across the industry, and as such we are not able to provide an accurate estimation before this date. The estimate for total demand across the nuclear industry (in Full Time Equivalents) for 2014 and 2015 is 70,000 and 77,000 respectively.</p><p> </p><p>The latest NWA published in July 2017 estimates the total demand each year to 2025 in FTEs as follows: <strong>2016 – </strong>84,000,<strong> 2017</strong> – 87,000; <strong>2018</strong> – 89,000; <strong>2019</strong> – 90,000; <strong>2020</strong> – 96,000; <strong>2021</strong> – 100,000; <strong>2022</strong> – 100,000; <strong>2023</strong> – 97,000; <strong>2024</strong> – 94,000; <strong>2025</strong> – 90,000.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-12-04T16:36:38.61Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795713/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795713/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795713/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-28","Nuclear Power: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate he has made of the number of people employed in the nuclear industry in each year since 2010; and what forecast he has made of the number of people employed in that industry in each year to 2025.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","116067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795714","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-01","<p>The Green Finance Taskforce is a voluntary group of senior leaders from the finance sector who will deliver recommendations to help Government accelerate the growth of green finance, deliver the investment required to meet our domestic carbon reduction targets and consolidate our leadership in financing international clean investment.</p><p> </p><p>No funding is allocated to the Taskforce or its Secretariat.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-12-01T10:45:57.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795714/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795714/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795714/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-28","Green Finance Task Force","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what funding his Department has allocated to the Green Finance Taskforce in each of the next three years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","116068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795715","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-06","<p>I refer the Hon Member to my answer of 5 December 2017 (UIN’s, 115927, 115928, 115929).</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","116071 ; 116074","2017-12-06T15:20:28.64Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795715/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795715/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795715/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-28","Electric Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the cost to the public purse is of (a) installing and (b) subsidising (i) uni-directional and (ii) bi-directional charge points for electric vehicles within the UK.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","116069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795716","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-05","<p>The Energy Company Obligation (ECO) requires energy companies to fund household energy efficiency improvements each year. 70% of ECO is currently focussed on improving the energy efficiency of low income and vulnerable households and we intend to consult on moving that to 100% for the next Obligation period. Combined with energy rebates under the Warm Home Discount scheme, this is at least £770m of support to low income and vulnerable households in 2017/18.</p><p> </p><p>In the Clean Growth Strategy, the Government committed to extend support for home energy efficiency out to 2028 at least as the current levels of ECO funding (£640m per annum), and review the best form of support beyond 2022 recognising the need to both save carbon and meet the Government’s commitment to upgrade all fuel poor homes to EPC Band C by 2030.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, Government has legislated from April 2018 that all landlords of the worst performing privately rented properties must meet a minimum standard of Energy Performance Certificate Band E, before they can be let. In the longer term, Government has committed to looking at raising energy performance standards across the private rented sector, with a view for as many properties to reach Energy Performance Certificate Band C by 2030.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-12-05T11:06:59.297Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795716/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795716/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795716/answer","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795716/answer/previousversion/26538","Biography information for Claire Perry","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-28","Energy: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps the Government is taking to upgrade fuel poor homes to Band C or above.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","116070"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795717","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-06","<p>I refer the Hon Member to my answer of 5 December 2017 (UIN’s, 115927, 115928, 115929).</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","116069 ; 116074","2017-12-06T15:20:28.687Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795717/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795717/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795717/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-28","Electric Vehicles: Charging Points","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the amount of money projected to be invest by 2025 in (a) installing and (b) subsidising (i) uni-directional and (ii) bi-directional charge points for electric vehicles within the UK; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","116071"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795718","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-05","<p>The figures below detail planned Government capital spending on flood and coastal erosion risk management in England. Contributions to flood or coastal defence improvements from other sources are not included. Budgets for 2021-22 and beyond have not been set.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>£ million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017/18</p></td><td><p>413.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2018/19</p></td><td><p>450.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2019/20</p></td><td><p>490.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2020/21</p></td><td><p>459.0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In addition to the capital spending outlined above, we will be spending over £1 billion on the maintenance of flood defence assets between 2015 and 2020.</p><p> </p><p>The figures in the (above) table vary from the published spending figures due to the autumn 2017 budget announcements, where an additional £76 million was allocated.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-12-05T17:53:17.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795718/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795718/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795718/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-28","Environment Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how much the Government plans to spend on flood and coastal erosion risk management in England in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","116072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795719","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-04","<p>The Clean Growth Strategy, published recently, sets out Government’s aspiration that as many homes as possible will be upgraded to an Energy Performance Certificate (EPC) band C by 2035 where practical, cost-effective and affordable. In the Clean Growth Strategy, we set out a number of policies and proposals that we will progress to meet this aspiration. For example, we:</p><p> </p><ol><li>Are supporting around £3.6 billion of investment to upgrade around a million homes through the Energy Company Obligation (ECO), and will extend support for home energy efficiency improvements until 2028 at the current level of ECO funding</li></ol><p> </p><ol start="2"><li>Will develop a long term trajectory to improve the energy performance standards of privately rented homes, with the aim of upgrading as many as possible to EPC Band C by 2030 where practical, cost-effective and affordable</li></ol><p> </p><ol start="3"><li>Will consult on how social housing can meet similar standards over this period</li></ol><p> </p><ol start="4"><li>Intend to consult on strengthening energy performance standards for new and existing homes under Building Regulations, including futureproofing new homes for low carbon heating systems, following the outcome of the independent review of Building Regulations and fire safety, and subject to its conclusions.</li></ol><p> </p><ol start="5"><li>Are seeking evidence on building a market for energy efficiency, including additional measures to improve energy performance of owner occupied homes through a Call for Evidence published alongside the Clean Growth Strategy.</li></ol><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-12-04T15:22:07.147Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795719/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795719/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795719/answer","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795719/answer/previousversion/26539","Biography information for Claire Perry","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-28","Energy: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what progress his Department is making on increasing the number of homes to be classified as EPC Band C by 2035.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","116073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795720","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-06","<p>I refer the Hon Member to my answer of 5 December 2017 (UIN’s, 115927, 115928, 115929).</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","116069 ; 116071","2017-12-06T15:20:28.737Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795720/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795720/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795720/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-28","Electric Vehicles: Charging Points","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the number of (a) uni-directional and (b) bi-directional charge points for electric vehicles installed in the UK by 2025; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","116074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795721","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-06","<p>I refer the Hon Member to my answer of 5 December 2017 (UIN 115930).</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-12-06T15:23:05.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795721/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795721/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795721/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-28","Motor Vehicles: Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with the exception of electric vehicles, what policies and options his Department has assessed as feasible routes to decarbonise petrol vehicles before 2040.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","116075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795722","HM Treasury","false","2017-12-05","<p>Support for bioethanol is informed by the provisions of the Renewable Energy and Energy Tax Directives. Together these have prompted support through a market based mechanism rather than the tax system. For further information about the government’s approach I refer the hon. Member to the answer given by my hon. Friend the member for Hereford and South Herefordshire (Jesse Norman) on 13 September 2017, UIN 8877.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","115926","2017-12-05T14:38:03.973Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795722/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795722/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795722/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-28","Biofuels: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the merits of taxing bioethanol on the basis of energy content rather than volume; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","116076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795723","Department of Health","false","2017-12-06","<p>NHS England advises that Herts Valleys Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG) has no current plans to sell the Hemel Hempstead hospital site, as it intends to use the existing site for new service provision as a local hospital/community hub under the Your Care, Your Future programme.</p><p> </p><p>There is a possibility that some land might become surplus, as there is potential to improve design efficiency, and therefore reduce the space requirement. Should that be the case, the land would be sold and the proceeds reinvested in local health services. Herts Valley CCG cannot confirm at this stage whether there will be surplus land and if so, what the proportion would be.</p><p> </p><p>Under current arrangements, where land or buildings are locally owned by a National Health Service trust or NHS foundation trust, the full capital receipt from its disposal is usually retained by that organisation to reinvest in the NHS in that area. This is set out in guidance to the NHS issued by NHS Improvement.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-12-06T12:13:36.32Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795723/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795723/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795723/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-28","Hemel Hempstead Hospital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of the proceeds from the sale of the existing Hemel Hempstead hospital site will be used to provide new hospital facilities in Hemel Hempstead.","false","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","Hemel Hempstead","Sir Mike  Penning","116077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795724","Department for Education","false","2017-12-06","<p>The Department published the outcomes of the consultation on implementing the English Baccalaureate (EBacc) on 19 July (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/implementing-the-english-baccalaureate" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/implementing-the-english-baccalaureate</a>) alongside its EBacc equality analysis (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/english-baccalaureate-equality-analysis" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/english-baccalaureate-equality-analysis</a>).</p><p>The EBacc policy aims to ensure that the vast majority of pupils, including those from disadvantaged backgrounds, take the EBacc subjects. Sutton Trust research<sup>1</sup> found that 300 secondary schools had transformed their Key Stage 4 curriculum between 2010 and 2013 in response to Government policy, achieving a rise in the proportion of pupils entering the EBacc from 8% to 48%. It also found that pupil premium students benefitted most from the changes at these schools.</p><p>The Department publishes entries into, and achievement of, the EBacc for pupils eligible for free school meals. A time series, with the latest available information (2015/16) can be be found in the ‘characteristics summary’ tab, of the ‘characteristics national tables: SFR03/2017’ at this link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/revised-gcse-and-equivalent-results-in-england-2015-to-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/revised-gcse-and-equivalent-results-in-england-2015-to-2016</a>.</p><ol><li>Sutton Trust: Changing the Subject, Rebecca Allen and Dave Thompson, July 2016 <a href="https://www.suttontrust.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/Changing-the-subject_V4-1.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.suttontrust.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/Changing-the-subject_V4-1.pdf</a>.</li></ol>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-12-06T16:58:41.363Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795724/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795724/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795724/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-28","English Baccalaureate: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent assessment has she made of the impact of the English Baccalaureate on improving the educational outcomes for children on Free School Meals.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","116078"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795725","Department for Education","false","2017-12-06","<p>For the current financial year 2017 to 2018, the pre-16 funding for secondary pupils is available at:<br><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/schools-block-funding-allocations-2017-to-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/schools-block-funding-allocations-2017-to-2018</a>.</p><p>Schools selective status is available at:<br>(<a href="https://get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/Downloads" target="_blank">https://get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/Downloads</a> using the ‘State-funded school ﬁelds CSV’ link).</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-12-06T17:00:26.223Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795725/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795725/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795725/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-28","Pupils: Per Capita Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much funding per pupil did (a) free (b) academy (c) comprehensive, and (d) grammar schools receive in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","116079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795726","Department for Education","false","2017-12-06","<p>The information is published in the underlying data: SFR28/2017 of the annual ‘Schools, pupils and their characteristics’ statistical release.</p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-pupils-and-their-characteristics-january-2017" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-pupils-and-their-characteristics-january-2017</a>.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-12-06T17:07:28.773Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795726/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795726/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795726/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-28","Pupils: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of pupils in receipt of free school meals attend (a) Free Schools, (b) academies, (c) comprehensives and (d) grammar schools.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","116080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795727","Department for Education","false","2017-12-06","<p>This information could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-12-06T16:53:07.663Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795727/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795727/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795727/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-28","English Baccalaureate","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of English Baccalaureate students went on to (a) A-levels (b) vocational study and (c) an apprenticeship in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","116081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795728","HM Treasury","false","2017-12-04","<p>We have made significant progress in reducing the deficit from its post-war peak of 9.9% of GDP in 2009-10 to 2.3% of GDP in 2016-17. The Office for Budget Responsibility forecasts it will fall further to 1.6% of GDP in 2019-20.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-12-04T14:30:56.263Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795728/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795728/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795728/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-28","Public Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the budget deficit was in 2010; what his most recent estimate of the budget deficit is; and what forecast he has made of the budget deficit in 2019.","false","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","116082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795730","Department of Health","false","2017-12-06","<p>As part of the Your Care, Your Future programme, the Board of West Hertfordshire Hospitals NHS Trust approved the Trust’s Strategic Outline Case identifying options for investment in the Trust’s estate in February 2017. The Board approved two options to be worked up in more detail; both would continue to use Watford General Hospital as the location of emergency and specialist care, with St Albans City Hospital further developed as a planned care centre.</p><p> </p><p>Your Care, Your Future includes plans to develop new pathways for care in the community, for example through local general practitioner surgeries and specialised hubs. The plans include the redevelopment of the Hemel Hempstead Hospital as a local hospital/community hub.</p><p> </p><p>Herts Valley Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG) is currently developing the clinical model of service provision, but the CCG sees the new facility as providing a wide range of health and social care services, including: voluntary and community services, community physical and mental health services and planned care, and outpatient and diagnostic provision.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-12-06T12:19:16.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795730/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795730/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795730/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-28","Health Services: Hertfordshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what NHS services he expects to be available to residents of Hemel Hempstead from the new facilities to be provided by (a) West Hertfordshire Hospitals NHS Trust, (b) Hertfordshire Community NHS Trust,  and (c) Hertfordshire Partnership University NHS Foundation Trust.","false","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","Hemel Hempstead","Sir Mike  Penning","116083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795731","Department for Education","false","2017-12-06","<p>This information could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-12-06T16:26:50.067Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795731/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795731/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795731/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-28","English Baccalaureate: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of English Baccalaureate students in receipt of free school meals went on to (a) A-levels, (b) vocational study, and (c) an apprenticeship in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","116084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795733","Department for Education","false","2017-12-06","<p>The Government published the English Baccalaureate (EBacc) consultation response on 19 July 2017. It set out our ambition for 75% of year 10 pupils in state-funded mainstream schools studying GCSEs in the EBacc combination of subjects by September 2022. This is considered an important stepping stone to reaching 90% of year 10 pupils studying GCSEs in the EBacc subjects by 2025.</p><p> </p><p>Changes to school performance measures, relating to the EBacc, were clearly outlined in the Government response to the EBacc consultation. This can be viewed here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/implementing-the-english-baccalaureate" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/implementing-the-english-baccalaureate</a>.</p><p> </p><p>A list of groups representing employers who submitted responses to the consultation on implementing the EBacc, is published in the government response to the consultation.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-12-06T17:23:17.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795733/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795733/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795733/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-28","English Baccalaureate","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what information has been issued to employers on the English Baccalaureate performance measure.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","116085"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795734","Department for Education","false","2017-12-06","<p>We published the English Baccalaureate (EBacc) consultation response on 19 July 2017, which sets out the Government’s ambition that 75% of year 10 pupils in state-funded mainstream schools will start to study GCSEs in the EBacc combination of subjects by September 2022, as an important stepping stone to reaching 90% of year 10 pupils studying GCSEs in the EBacc subjects by 2025.</p><p> </p><p>Changes to school performance measures, relating to the EBacc, were clearly outlined in the Government response to the EBacc consultation, which can be viewed here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/implementing-the-english-baccalaureate" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/implementing-the-english-baccalaureate</a>.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-12-06T17:02:18.223Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795734/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795734/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795734/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-28","English Baccalaureate","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what information has been issued to Russell Group Universities on the English Baccalaureate performance measure.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","116086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795735","Department for Education","false","2017-12-06","<p>The number and proportion of pupils achieving the English Baccalaureate between 2009/10 and 2016/17 can be obtained from the Department’s statistical first releases at this link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-gcses-key-stage-4" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-gcses-key-stage-4</a>. The main tables for each year contain the required information (a time series is also available in the 2016/17 publication).</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-12-06T17:04:57.62Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795735/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795735/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795735/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-28","English Baccalaureate","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of trends in the proportion of students that obtain the English Baccalaureate in the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","116087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795736","Department for Education","false","2017-12-06","<p>The number and proportion of pupils obtaining the English Baccalaureate in state-funded schools and independent schools can be obtained from the Department’s statistical first releases at this link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-gcses-key-stage-4" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-gcses-key-stage-4</a>. The main tables for each year contain the required information.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-12-06T17:24:55.863Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795736/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795736/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795736/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-28","English Baccalaureate","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of students who obtain the English Baccalaureate attend (a) state and (b) independent schools.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","116088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795738","Department for Education","false","2017-12-06","<p>The department are working with the Department of Health and relevant delivery partners to finalise the funding arrangements for new pre-registration dental hygiene and dental therapy students starting courses on or after 1 August 2018.</p><p>We will confirm the funding arrangements in due course.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-12-06T16:47:50.13Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795738/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795738/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795738/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-28","Dentistry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when she plans to publish the funding arrangements for new pre-registration dental hygiene and dental therapy students starting courses on or after 1 August 2018.","false","Biography information for Stephen Morgan","Portsmouth South","Stephen Morgan","116089"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795739","Department for Transport","false","2017-12-06","<p>The Department’s Access Fund in 2016 was promoted as funding access to new and existing employment, training, and education. During the competition, the Department welcomed bids for funding that supported or developed Wheels to Work schemes in their area. Schemes which benefited from the Access Fund include Wheels 2 Work Leicestershire and Rutland.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-12-06T16:12:31.963Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795739/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795739/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795739/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-28","Wheels to Work Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what representations he has received on funding of Wheels to Work schemes: and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","116090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795741","HM Treasury","false","2017-12-01","<p>The Treasury receives a range of representations on various issues including business rates as part of the policy making process.</p><p> </p><p>Business rates are based on valuations from the Valuation Office Agency and the Government does not intervene in their independent assessments. The Valuation for Rating (Plant and Machinery) (England) Regulations 2000 set out when plant and machinery, including solar panels, are rateable.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-12-01T14:14:15.867Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795741/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795741/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795741/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-28","Solar Power: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent representations he has received from the solar power industry on how rooftop solar power is treated in business rates.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","116092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795742","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-12-01","<p>My Department does not hold information on business rates liabilities. Business rates are based on valuations from the Valuation Office Agency and we are not involved in their independent assessments.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-12-01T14:17:32.907Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795742/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795742/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795742/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-28","Solar Power: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the difference in business rate liabilities is for rooftop solar power where the majority of the power produced is (a) exported to a third party and (b) consumed onsite.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","116093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795743","HM Treasury","false","2017-12-01","<p>Business rates liabilities are based on the rateable value and the non-domestic rating multiplier set by the Government.</p><p> </p><p>The Valuation Office Agency (VOA) determines the rateable value of the property using three broad methods: a rentals basis; receipts and expenditure (R&amp;E); and a contractor’s basis, that is to say, a building's replacement costs. Rating case law requires that a hierarchy of use is adopted, in the order shown above; i.e. only when a rentals basis is not possible should the valuer adopt R&amp;E, with the contractor’s basis being the method of last resort.</p><p> </p><p>Solar panels are valued using either the R&amp;E method or the contractor’s basis, depending on the circumstances.</p><p> </p><p>Good quality CHP is partially-exempt from rating. The rateable parts are valued using either the R&amp;E method or the contractor’s basis, depending on the circumstances.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, if the solar panels or good quality CHP is a qualifying microgeneration (below 50kW) installation there is a temporary exemption from rating which means new schemes aren't assessed until the next revaluation takes place.‎</p><p> </p><p>Battery storage technologies are valued using the contractor's basis.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","116096","2017-12-01T14:09:03.92Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795743/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795743/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795743/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-28","Renewable Energy: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what methodology is used to calculate the business rate liabilities of (a) solar power and (b) Good Quality gas CHP; and what the rationale is for that methodology.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","116094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795745","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-07","<p>The welfare of gamebirds is protected by the Animal Welfare Act 2006. The statutory Code of Practice for the Welfare of Gamebirds Reared for Sporting Purposes provides keepers with guidance on how to meet the welfare needs of their gamebirds, as required by the Act. The Code recommends that barren cages for breeding pheasants and small barren cages for breeding partridges should not be used and that any system should be appropriately enriched. The Act and Defra’s Code are enforced by the Animal and Plant Health Agency.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-12-07T17:55:39.773Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795745/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795745/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795745/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-28","Game: Animal Welfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps his Department takes to (a) enforce the Welfare Code for game birds and (b) ensure that cages used for breeding pheasants and partridges meet animal welfare standards.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","116095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795746","HM Treasury","false","2017-12-01","<p>Business rates liabilities are based on the rateable value and the non-domestic rating multiplier set by the Government.</p><p> </p><p>The Valuation Office Agency (VOA) determines the rateable value of the property using three broad methods: a rentals basis; receipts and expenditure (R&amp;E); and a contractor’s basis, that is to say, a building's replacement costs. Rating case law requires that a hierarchy of use is adopted, in the order shown above; i.e. only when a rentals basis is not possible should the valuer adopt R&amp;E, with the contractor’s basis being the method of last resort.</p><p> </p><p>Solar panels are valued using either the R&amp;E method or the contractor’s basis, depending on the circumstances.</p><p> </p><p>Good quality CHP is partially-exempt from rating. The rateable parts are valued using either the R&amp;E method or the contractor’s basis, depending on the circumstances.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, if the solar panels or good quality CHP is a qualifying microgeneration (below 50kW) installation there is a temporary exemption from rating which means new schemes aren't assessed until the next revaluation takes place.‎</p><p> </p><p>Battery storage technologies are valued using the contractor's basis.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","116094","2017-12-01T14:09:03.967Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795746/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795746/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795746/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-28","Energy: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how battery storage technologies installed in commercial premises are assessed for business rates.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","116096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795747","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-01","<p>Solar power is a UK success story, with rapid deployment over the last 7 years. Latest figures indicate that we now have over 12.5GW of solar capacity installed in the UK, enough to power over 2.7 million homes and exceeding our historic projections.</p><p> </p><p>Costs for solar installations have fallen rapidly during this period, allowing both domestic and industrial consumers to benefit from increasingly cheap and clean electricity. We expect subsidy-free solar to be an increasingly attractive option, with the first subsidy-free UK solar farm recently deploying. Some of the UK’s largest solar developers have said that they will be installing and connecting subsidy-free sites over the next 12 months.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-12-01T13:34:50.05Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795747/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795747/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795747/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-28","Solar Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of the industrial benefits of solar power.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","116097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795748","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-01","<p>The report on the Future Capabilities of the UK Steel Sector is being finalised, following consultation with the UK steel industry. The Department aims to publish the findings once the report has been completed.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-12-01T10:43:40.957Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795748/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795748/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795748/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-28","Iron and Steel: Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 8 September 2017 to Question 7012, on iron and steel, when he plans to publish his Department's paper, Future Capabilities of the UK Steel Sector.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","116098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795750","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-12-04","<p>The new supply chain programme is to be piloted in 2018 in the automotive sector and will provide training and streamline business processes, so that UK suppliers can match the best in Europe and secure a greater share of the expenditure of UK based vehicle makers. This initiative will help support the industry’s ambition to increase UK content in the supply chain from 44% to 50% by 2022. More detail on this will be announced shortly.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-12-04T11:47:27.24Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795750/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795750/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795750/answer","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795750/answer/previousversion/26535","Biography information for Claire Perry","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-28","Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to his oral contribution of 27 November 2017, Official Report, column 45, what specific financial incentives will be available to encourage suppliers to relocate to the UK.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","116099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795751","Home Office","false","2017-12-01","<p>There are no plans to develop an evidential roadside drug driving testing device.</p><p>We have developed mobile drug screening technology to support drug driving legislation. This was first introduced for police use in December 2014.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-12-01T13:51:30.133Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795751/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795751/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795751/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-28","Driving under Influence: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps his Department has taken to develop an evidential roadside test for people who drive under the influence of drugs; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","116100"
