"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795284","Cabinet Office","false","2017-12-11","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-12-11T16:39:22.93Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795284/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795284/answer","PQ115705.pdf","PQ115705.pdf","UKSA response","UKSA response","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795284/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-11-27","Arthritis: Death","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many people of each gender and age group have died as a result of complications arising from arthritis in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","115705"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795285","Department of Health","false","2017-12-05","<p>A search of the Department’s Ministerial correspondence database has identified four items of correspondence received since November 2016 about the availability of new medications to alleviate the condition of people with multiple sclerosis on the National Health Service. This figure represents correspondence received by the Department’s Ministerial correspondence unit only.</p><p> </p><p>There have also been two Lords Written Parliamentary Questions.</p><p> </p><p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence is currently developing guidance on the use of cladribine for treating multiple sclerosis and expects to publish final guidance on 6 December.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-12-05T16:49:43.207Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795285/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795285/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795285/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-27","Multiple Sclerosis: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what representations he has received on the availability of new medications to alleviate the condition of people with MS on the NHS.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","115706"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795286","Department of Health","false","2017-12-05","<p>In 1991 the Committee on Medical Aspects of Food Policy (COMA), the predecessor to Scientific Advisory Committee on Nutrition (SACN), recommended Reference Nutrient Intakes (RNI) for protein for children and adults. These were set to meet the needs of 97.5% of the population. COMA also advised that it was prudent for adults to avoid protein intakes of more than twice the RNI. Since then the Government has not issued any guidance on the risks of high protein food intake.</p><p> </p><p>The SACN advises United Kingdom Government on nutrition matters. The SACN has not been asked for advice on, nor undertaken a risk assessment of high protein intakes and has no plans to do so.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-12-05T13:42:48.893Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795286/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795286/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/795286/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-27","Health Education: Proteins","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether his Department has issued guidance on the risks of high protein food intake.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","115707"
